dxe5 {Typical structure with dxe5} e6 7. Bd3) (5... e6 6. Bb5 Qc7 7. O-O Bd6 {
preparing ...f7-f6.}) 6. c3 g6 7. Bb5 Bd7 {Black does not mind the exchange of
this bishop - it can be a problematic piece (Ganguly-Ponomariov)} 8. Nxd7 ({
Squeeze strategy} 8. Bxc6 $5 Bxc6 9. Nd2) 8... Qxd7 9. O-O Bg7 10. Nd2 O-O 11.
Qe2 (11. Nf3 {[%csl Ye5]}) 11... e6 12. Nb3 $5 {[%csl Yc5] anticipating the
minority attack/preventing ...Na5-c4 plan (Predke-Rodshtein)} a6 13. Bd3 {
White's bishop pair is not such an important factor in this structure since
black pawn chain limits white light-squared bishop. However, it can become
very important if the position opens up favorably for White.} Qc7 14. Bg5 Rac8
(14... e5 $5 15. dxe5 Nxe5 {Typical structure with the isolated queens' pawn}
16. Rad1 Rfe8 $11) (14... b5 {premature minority attack in the view of} 15. a4
$1 b4 16. Nc5 bxc3 17. bxc3 a5 18. Rab1) 15. h3 Rfe8 16. f4 Nd7 17. Qf3 Qd6 18.
Bh4 b5 (18... f5 {Typical strategy with ...f7-f5 (Carlsen-Vidit)} 19. g4 b5)
19. f5 $5 (19. a3 $14 Nb6 20. Qf2 Nc4 21. Nc5) 19... gxf5 $6 (19... exf5 20. g4
(20. Bg3 Qf6 21. Qxd5 Nb6) 20... fxg4 21. Qxf7+ (21. hxg4 $44) 21... Kh8 $13)
20. g4 Nf6 $2 (20... Ne7 21. Bg3 $36) 21. Rae1 $40 Kh8 22. Bg3 fxg4 23. hxg4 e5
24. Qf5 Ne7 25. Qxe5 Qd7 26. Qg5 Neg8 (26... Qxg4 27. Qxg4 Nxg4 28. Nc5 $18)
27. Bf5 $18 Qd8 28. Bxc8 Rxe1 29. Rxe1 Qxc8 30. Qf5 Qc6 31. Bf4 h6 32. Nc5 Bf8
33. Nd3 Ne7 34. Qxf6+ 1-0

