{[%evp 0,61,38,13,66,60,70,35,43,28,28,10,29,2,10,10,43,6,1,22,22,19,5,16,16,
-6,28,29,26,27,27,34,35,37,25,-3,60,41,40,31,24,3,42,-15,-9,0,7,0,0,0,0,-6,-13,
-8,-5,0,9,17,31,24,20,21,-5,8]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3
Qc7 6. h3 {prophylaxis against ...Bg4} (6. Ne2 Bg4) 6... Nf6 7. Nf3 g6 8. Qc2 {
prophylaxis against ...Bf5} (8. O-O Bf5 9. Bxf5 gxf5 {typical structure with
gxf5 (Van Foreest-Anand)}) 8... Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 $14 {...e7-e5 and ...
Bc8-f5/g4 are under control - White has a typical positional squeeze in the
exchange variation. Black has a problematic piece in the light-squared bishop.}
Nh5 11. Be3 Bd7 (11... Nf4 $5 12. Bf1 Bf5 13. Qd2 Nh5 14. Qd1 Nf6 15. Nbd2 $14)
12. Na3 $5 {Sometimes the knight is well developed here in the exchange
variation.} (12. Nbd2) 12... a6 13. Qd2 Rfe8 {[#]} (13... b5 14. Nc2 Na5 15. b3
Rfc8 16. Nb4 $1 e6 17. Rac1 $16) 14. g4 $1 {A start of the strong,
space-grabbing strategy.} Nf6 15. Bf4 Qb6 16. Ne5 $36 {An obvious positional
initiative for White - Black is solid, but seems to lack a clear plan.} Rad8
17. f3 Bc8 $6 {A passive move, Black struggles to find a good employment for
his light-squared bishop.} (17... Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Bc6 19. Rae1 $14) 18. Qh2 $1 {
A lovely queen maneuver, increasing control over e5-outpost.} Be6 $6 {The
bishop is poorly placed here.} 19. Re2 ({White could have obtained a
strategically nearly winning position with} 19. Nxc6 Qxc6 20. Nc2 $16 {[%cal
Gh3h5,Re7e5,Rb7b5,Gf3f4,Gf4e5]}) 19... Rc8 20. Be3 Nd7 21. f4 Ndxe5 22. fxe5 f6
$132 23. exf6 exf6 24. Rae1 Bf7 25. Kh1 Re7 26. Bc1 Rxe2 27. Rxe2 Na5 28. Qg2
Qd8 29. Re1 Qd7 30. Bf4 Bf8 31. Nc2 1/2-1/2

