{[%evp 0,94,24,11,54,60,70,42,54,35,39,31,31,7,7,7,-3,-14,0,-2,7,7,4,-24,-3,-1,
7,12,-2,15,14,6,29,13,27,12,26,-56,3,-38,-91,-84,-84,-68,-49,-52,-81,-81,-75,
-81,-89,-106,-83,-87,-71,-87,-70,-78,-87,-85,-89,-89,-35,-156,-116,-102,-93,
-95,-129,-130,-138,-115,-107,-173,-174,-174,-163,-175,-188,-213,-211,-239,-225,
-284,-259,-259,-251,-272,-247,-295,-309,-310,-317,-318,-317,-588,-605]} 1. e4
c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bb5 e6 6. Ne5 Bd7 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 8. c3 Nf6
9. O-O Bd6 10. Nd2 O-O 11. f4 {White prepares the typical attacking scheme,
while also increasing control over e5-outpost. Downside: permanently weakens
e4-square.} (11. Nb3 {was the strategy in Berg-Salem.}) 11... Qc7 12. g3 a6 13.
Bd3 b5 {Typical strategy: minority attack.} 14. a3 Na5 {Typical strategy:
knight to the c4-outpost.} 15. Qe2 Nc4 16. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3e5] [#]} Qb7 $1 {
Typical strategy: knight to the e4-outpost.} ({Alternative way to take control
over e4-outpost.} 16... Be7 $5 17. Ne5 Nd6) 17. Ne5 Rac8 {preparing ...Ne4.} (
17... g6 $6 {creates a hook for the kingside attack after} 18. g4 $40 {[%cal
Gf4f5] as in Berg-Salem.}) 18. f5 $6 {This looks dangerous, but White is not
ready to open the position as black pieces are placed better.} (18. Re1 Be7 $5
19. a4 Nd6 20. Be3 Nfe4 $15) 18... exf5 19. Rxf5 Bxe5 $1 20. dxe5 Ne4 {The
complete success of Black's strategy. Knights dominate the bishop pair and
e5-pawn is weak.} 21. Be3 g6 22. Bxc4 $1 bxc4 (22... gxf5 $6 23. Bb3 $44) 23.
Rff1 Rfe8 24. Bd4 Rb8 $17 {Black has a clear positional advantage: weak b2 and
e5 pawns, powerful Ne4. White tried to create practical chances, but Black won
without much trouble.} 25. Qg4 Qe7 26. Qe2 Qg5 27. Rae1 Rb7 28. Qg2 Reb8 29.
Re2 h5 30. Rf4 h4 31. Rxh4 Rxb2 32. Rxb2 Qc1+ 33. Qf1 Qxf1+ 34. Kxf1 Rxb2 35.
a4 Ra2 36. e6 fxe6 37. Rh8+ Kf7 38. Rh7+ Ke8 39. g4 g5 40. h4 gxh4 41. Rxh4
Ng3+ 42. Ke1 e5 43. Ba7 Ra1+ 44. Kd2 Ne4+ 45. Kc2 Ra2+ 46. Kc1 Nxc3 47. Rh6 d4
0-1

