{[%evp 0,58,19,29,65,74,57,53,53,41,33,23,31,24,39,25,59,25,40,34,32,36,37,17,
39,20,12,12,12,6,13,9,18,10,10,-16,-14,-14,-15,-10,-25,-45,-14,-171,-165,-177,
-181,-224,-224,-156,-285,-363,-363,-275,-207,-190,-147,-352,-393,-382,-394]} 1.
e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. Ne2 Bg4 7. O-O e6 8. Qe1
Be7 $5 (8... Nf6 9. f3 (9. Bg5 $5) 9... Bh5 10. Qh4) 9. Bf4 Qb6 10. Nd2 Nf6 11.
Rb1 O-O 12. h3 (12. Ng3 Nh5 13. Nxh5 Bxh5) 12... Bh5 13. Ng3 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6
{While the exchange of light-squared bishops is generally a strategic
achievement for Black in such positions, he should still not relax because the
pawn on g6 provides a hook for White's attack with h3-h4-h5.} 15. Qe2 a5 $1 {
preparing ...Qa6, offering the queen trade and speeding up the minority attack.
} 16. h4 Qa6 {Acquiescing to the queen trade would be a defeat to White's
attacking ambitions. In that sense, Singer's refusal to trade is
understandable. It is also unlikely that he had anticipated Eljanov's
defensive idea when playing} 17. Qf3 $6 ({Objectively speaking, better was} 17.
a4 $11) 17... Nh7 $1 {This defensive move is based on a wonderful tactical
idea.} 18. Qg4 (18. h5 {is obviously met by} g5 {so White tries to take
g5-square under control before pushing the h-pawn.}) 18... b5 19. Rfe1 ({
The most direct attempt at attack} 19. Nf3 b4 20. h5 {is refuted by} f5 $1 21.
Qxg6 (21. Qh3 g5 $19) 21... Rf6 {and the White queen gets trapped! Without
being able to push h4-h5, White's attack has hit a brick wall and Black has a
free hand on the queenside.}) 19... b4 20. Re3 a4 21. a3 {A desperate attempt
to deflect the bishop from e7. Eljanov calls the bluff.} bxa3 22. bxa3 Bxa3 23.
h5 {[#] White counted on Black not being able to play 23...g5 now, but he
forgot about:} f5 $1 24. Qf3 ({After} 24. Qxg6 Rf6 $19 {the queen gets trapped
the same way as in 19.Nf3 line.}) 24... g5 $19 {Black's counterattack is
decisive.} 25. Bd6 Bxd6 26. Rxe6 Bxg3 27. Qxd5 Rad8 28. Qc5 Qd3 29. fxg3 Nxd4
0-1

