1. e4 (1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Nge2
Re8 8. O-O a6 9. Bd2 Bd6 10. f3 {[%cal Ge3e4]} c5 $1 $132 {is a similar
position to the one that arises in our example, only with colors reversed.})
1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. h3 e6 {Black abandons
the idea to develop the bishop to f5 and simply goes for ...Bd6, ...Nge7, ...
f6 setup.} 7. Nf3 Bd6 8. O-O Nge7 9. Re1 a6 10. Nbd2 f6 11. c4 $1 {A
principled way to prevent the ...e6-e5 break. This idea is often met with
colors reversed in certain Nimzo-Indian/QGD structures.} ({In case of passive
play as in the following variation} 11. Nf1 O-O 12. Ne3 Bd7 13. Qe2 {Black can
activate the light-squared bishop with the maneuver} Be8 $1 $132 {[%cal Ge8h5]}
) 11... O-O 12. a3 Ng6 13. Nf1 Qf7 $1 {Improving queen's position as f7 looks
like the safest square for it.} 14. Bd2 {Both sides have a difficult time
releasing tension in the center, so we have a classical maneuvering game -
trying to improve their pieces before taking concrete actions.} (14. Ng3 Nce7
$1 $13 (14... Bd7 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Nf5 $14)) 14... Nf4 {Using a temporary
lack of coordination between white pieces to win the bishop pair.} 15. Bxf4
Bxf4 {Optically, White may stand slightly better but black position is very
solid and flexible.} 16. Ne3 Kh8 17. Qc2 g6 18. Re2 (18. Bf1 Bd7 19. g3 Bd6 20.
Bg2 Rac8 $11) 18... Bd7 19. cxd5 exd5 20. Rae1 Rad8 21. Qc5 Be6 22. Nd1 (22.
Bxa6 Rc8 23. Bd3 Ne5 24. Qb5 Nxf3+ 25. gxf3 Bb8 $44) 22... Bd6 23. Qb6 Bc7 24.
Qb3 Bc8 $11 25. Ne3 Bb8 26. Qc3 Bd7 27. Qb3 Bc8 28. Qc3 Bd7 29. Bb1 Bd6 1/2-1/2

