{[%evp 0,56,19,29,65,74,61,47,47,30,17,33,33,17,41,17,60,39,44,44,61,61,44,40,
29,29,22,21,32,13,46,-8,-15,-14,-14,-21,-8,-3,-20,-36,-18,-14,-23,-91,-91,-118,
-103,-197,-249,-241,-247,-228,-276,-361,-362,-360,-379,-370,-364]} 1. e4 c6 2.
d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. c3 Qc7 6. h3 g6 7. Nf3 (7. Qc2 {seems like a
better idea here now that Black does not have ...f7-f6 option.}) 7... Bf5 8.
Ne5 Nc6 9. Bf4 Qb6 10. Bxf5 gxf5 {A typical structure with ...gxf5. Black
exchanged his most problematic piece at the expense of his pawn structure.
However, the semi-open g-file and e4-outpost could provide good positional
compensation.} 11. Nd3 {[#]} e6 $6 (11... Rg8 {immediately was more accurate!})
12. Nd2 $6 (12. g4 $1 {seems like a more principled choice, as in
Dominguez-Mamedyarov} fxg4 13. hxg4 Rg8 14. f3 $14) 12... Rg8 $1 13. O-O {
A risky decision considering the rook on g8.} ({The thematic move} 13. g4 $1 {
was probably better even at a cost of a pawn:} fxg4 14. hxg4 Rxg4 15. Qf3 h5
16. O-O-O $44) 13... O-O-O 14. a4 Ne4 {Utilizing the e4-outpost.} 15. Rc1 $6 {
Too slow.} (15. Qh5 $1 {would still keep Black on his toes.}) 15... Bd6 $1 {
Exchanging an important attacking and defensive piece.} 16. Bxd6 Nxd6 $11 {
The black king is safe now and even though the position is roughly equal, it
is easier to play for Black since he controls the only open file.} 17. b4 Kb8
18. Qe2 Qc7 19. Qe3 Ne7 {Slowly moving pieces toward the kingside.} 20. f3 $2 {
Too weakening, panicky move.} (20. Kh1 Ne4 21. Nc5 Ng6 22. Ndxe4 dxe4 23. a5
Nf4 24. Rg1 $13) 20... Ng6 21. Ne5 f4 22. Qe1 Nf5 $19 23. Nxg6 Rxg6 24. Rf2
Rdg8 25. c4 Ne3 26. cxd5 Nxg2 27. Qe5 Qxe5 28. dxe5 Ne1+ 0-1

