{[%evp 0,24,19,31,75,68,58,58,56,33,36,15,50,20,42,35,53,64,53,48,63,48,47,40,
37,12,48]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. h3 g6 7. Ne2
Bf5 8. Bxf5 gxf5 9. Bf4 Qd7 10. Nd2 e6 11. g4 $1 {Dominguez does not miss the
opportunity to strike at the f5-pawn.} ({Instead, static play with} 11. O-O Bd6
12. Nf3 O-O-O $13 {could lead to a type of position similar to the previous
game where Black's chances are not worse.}) 11... Nge7 12. Ng3 $1 {Forcing a
favorable transformation of the pawn structure. Here we see one advantage of
having the knight on e2 instead of f3.} O-O-O (12... fxg4 13. hxg4 $16 {
leaves the h7-pawn desperately weak.}) 13. gxf5 Nxf5 14. Nxf5 exf5 $16 {
The black pawn structure is atrocious. A slight lead in development does not
compensate for this long-term weakness.} 15. Qf3 (15. Qh5 $5 {putting pressure
on all three black pawns.} Re8+ 16. Kd1 $16) 15... Re8+ 16. Kd1 Re6 17. Kc2 Ne7
18. Rhe1 Ng6 19. Rxe6 (19. Be5 $5 Nxe5 20. Rxe5 Rxe5 21. dxe5 Bc5 22. Nb3 $16)
19... fxe6 {White is still positionally better in the final position where the
draw was agreed.} 1/2-1/2

