{[#]} 16. Nd4 Bh7 17. Bd3 {Sooner or later, White would have to exchange the
powerful light-squared bishop.} Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Nc4 {c4-outpost} 19. Qe2 Qb6 {
Trying to provoke a weakness with b2-b3 - then c3-pawn would be weak.} 20. Rab1
{[#]} Na5 $1 {An instructive maneuver - the d4-knight is strong, we should
exchange it.} ({Black would also be fine in case of} 20... O-O 21. f4 f6 $11 {
but why tolerate the knight on d4?}) 21. f4 g6 $1 {A classical strategy of
limitation on the kingside: putting pawns on g6-h5. The black king is safe in
the center.} 22. Kh1 Nc6 23. Rbd1 h5 24. Qf2 Nxd4 25. Rxd4 Rc8 $11 {The
position is objectively equal, but Black has somewhat better practical chances
due to a more stable pawn chain and minority attack ideas.} 26. h3 Rc6 27. Rfd1
Qc7 28. R1d2 Rc4 29. Rxc4 Qxc4 30. a3 Qe4 31. Re2 Qc4 32. Rd2 Qe4 33. Re2 Qd3
34. Rd2 Qb1+ 35. Qg1 Qe4 36. Qf2 O-O 37. Rd4 Qb1+ 38. Kh2 Rc8 39. Qd2 b5 $15 {
The minority attack starts.} 40. Qf2 Qc1 41. Qd2 Qb1 42. Qf2 a5 43. Qd2 Kg7 44.
Qf2 Qf5 45. Qe3 Qc2 46. Rd2 $2 {Losing coordination of heavy pieces.} (46. Qd2
{would still hold the position.}) 46... Qb1 {Now the 4th rank and the b4-break
cannot be properly defended.} 47. Qf2 b4 $1 {A timely breakthrough.} 48. axb4
axb4 49. cxb4 Rc1 {Weak white king is the ultimate target.} 50. b5 Rf1 51. Qe3
h4 52. g4 Rh1+ 0-1

