1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Bd3 Qc7 6. Na3 a6 7. Nc2 Nf6 8. h3
e5 $5 {A typical idea to gain more space for black pieces at the expense of
being saddled with the isolated queen's pawn. While White is generally
slightly better in such positions, Black has a large reserve of solidity and
fairly active piece play. Grischuk's play in this game is exemplary.} 9. dxe5
Nxe5 10. Nf3 Bd6 {This is the best diagonal for the bishop. It should be
preserved from the exchange for as long as possible.} ({Black achieves nothing
with the following exchange} 10... Nxd3+ 11. Qxd3 Bc5 12. Be3 $14) 11. Nxe5 (
11. O-O O-O 12. Bg5 Ne4 $1 $132 {The e4-outpost (as well as the one on c4) are
important in this typical structure.}) 11... Bxe5 12. O-O O-O 13. Qf3 Re8 14.
Re1 ({More accurate seems to be} 14. Be3 Bd7 15. Rfe1 h6 16. Rad1 Rad8 $14 {/=}
(16... Ne4 $2 17. Nb4 $1 $16)) 14... Bh2+ $1 15. Kh1 Rxe1+ 16. Nxe1 Be5 {
Black disrupted White's piece coordination and won an important tempo for
development.} 17. Be3 Bd7 18. Nc2 Re8 19. Bd4 (19. Re1 {is more accurate, but
Black is very solid nevertheless. For example} Ba4 20. Re2 h6 21. Bd4 Ne4 $132)
19... Bxd4 20. Nxd4 {White obtained full control over the d4-outpost, but
Black can play around the strong knight:} Qb6 $1 {targeting b2-pawn.} 21. Rb1
Ne4 $11 {Black has already solved all potential problems with the IQP thanks
to the active piece play} 22. Bxe4 dxe4 {A favorable exchange of the pawn
structure.} 23. Qf4 h6 24. Kg1 $2 {A blitz blunder.} e3 $1 25. fxe3 Bxh3 $17 {
Black was even winning, but this being a blitz game, anything is possible and
Carlsen eventually prevailed.} 26. Rf1 Qg6 27. Qf3 Bc8 28. Qd5 b5 29. e4 Qxe4
30. Qxf7+ Kh7 31. Qf3 Qg6 32. a3 Re5 33. Qc6 Qxc6 34. Nxc6 Rg5 35. Rf2 h5 36.
Rd2 Bb7 37. Nd4 Bd5 38. Nc2 Bb7 39. Ne3 Re5 40. Kf2 Re6 41. c4 bxc4 42. Nxc4
Rf6+ 43. Kg1 Kh6 44. b4 g5 45. a4 h4 46. b5 axb5 47. axb5 Kh5 48. Nd6 Ba8 49.
b6 Kg4 50. Kh2 Re6 51. b7 Bxb7 52. Nxb7 Re3 53. Nd6 Ra3 54. Rd4+ Kh5 55. Rd5
Kg6 56. Ne4 1-0

