1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 {The two knights variation has become an
increasingly popular approach for White against the Caro Kann these days. It
usually leads to less theoretically less explored positions compared to the
advanced variation (3.e5) and open variation (3.Nc3/Nd2), but still with
chances for White to obtain an advantage out of the opening.} dxe4 {Nowadays,
most players lean toward this continuation. In fact, I was one of the first
players to start employing it on the top level.} ({For many years,} 3... Bg4 {
has been considered to be the main option and the most principled way to meet
two knights variation. Yet, it has come out of fashion recently because it is
not clear how exactly Black equalizes is several critical lines. In principle,
Black is ready to give up the bishop pair after} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 {
which he compensates for with a rock-solid pawn center and a closed type of
position in which white bishops do not have as much impact as the knights.} (
5... Nf6 {is also possible, but 5...e6 is more flexible as the knight is
sometimes better developed to e7 and the bishop to g7.}) {White has tried many
ideas here, 6.d4 is the most classical one, but recently the flexible approach
with 6.g3 or 6.Be2, keeping both d2-d3 and d2-d4 options open, have become
very popular for White.} 6. g3 $5 {The 'Reti' approach with the kingside
fianchetto is the one that I would prefer for White.} ({These days, the most
fashionable, however, is} 6. Be2 {The idea is to keep options with the d-pawn
open.} Bc5 {is again the most typical move among several alternatives, as
Black actively fights for the d4-square. I have played this move against the
French IM Bailet with success.} ({In case of} 6... Nf6 7. O-O Nbd7 {White can
play} 8. d4 {with a typical slight positional plus due to the space advantage
and the bishop pair.}) 7. O-O Nf6 (7... Ne7 {is one of the typical developing
options for Black, but here it is strongly met by} 8. Na4 $1 {when White wins
the fight for the d4-square.} dxe4 9. Qxe4 Bd6 10. d4 $14 {In general, this
type of position is slightly preferable for White thanks to the bishop pair.
However, if Black manages to exchange the dark-squared bishops, the position
becomes more or less equal.}) (7... Nd7 8. Qg3 $5 Bd4 9. d3 Ne7 10. Bd1 $5 O-O
11. Ne2 $36) 8. Rd1 Bd4 (8... d4 9. e5 Nfd7 10. Ne4) 9. Qf4 $1 {The most
principled move, fighting for the d4-square even at the cost of a pawn.} ({
In my game, White continued} 9. exd5 cxd5 (9... exd5 $5 {is also playable for
Black.}) 10. Nb5 Bb6 11. c4 $6 {This was not a good move} ({A normal
continuation would be} 11. d4 Nc6 12. c3 $11 {with a good version of the
exchange variation for Black.}) {because after} 11... a6 12. Nc3 Nc6 13. cxd5
Nd4 {Black was in full control of d4-square.} 14. Qg3 O-O 15. d3 Nxd5 16. Bf3
Bc7 17. Qg4 Nf6 18. Bg5 Nxg4 19. Bxd8 Nxf3+ 20. gxf3 Bh2+ {0-1 (20) Bailet, P 
(2501)-Eljanov,P (2702) Brest 2018}) 9... dxe4 $5 {This is the safe option
that I would recommend for Black. It was played by GM Alexander Riazantsev, a
well-known expert in the Caro-Kann.} ({The main line is} 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3
Nxe4 {but this can be dangerous for Black as he falls behind with his
development. White has a choice of attacking options} 11. Ba3 (11. Rb1 $5 {
is not so popular, but it makes sense.} Qe7 ({Alternatives are} 11... b6 12.
Ba3) ({and} 11... b5) 12. Bf3 Ng5 13. Bh5 O-O 14. d3 f6 15. Qa4 $44 {[%cal
Gc1a3] This position happened in the game Paehtz,E (2484)-Gunina,V (2509)
Monaco 2019 1-0 (53). Only for one pawn, White has more than enough initiative
and black position is quite unpleasant. Very precise defense is required.})
11... Nd7 12. Rab1 {Black should play very carefully here because the margin
of error is very small. If you would like to play this line as Black, you have
to analyze and remember many sharp variations precisely.} Qa5 (12... b6 $5 {
is an alternative that was tried in some recent games with success for Black.}
