Black has a reliable position.}) (10. Qd4 Bf5 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 e6 13. O-O
Nf6 $11) 10... Nf6 $5 {This retreat is the best choice if Black is happy with
a move repetition.} (10... a5 $5 {is a reasonable alternative, trying to
provoke a weakness on b4 if White goes 11.a4.} 11. a3 (11. c4 Nf6 12. Qe3 Bf5
13. Nh4 Bg6 $11) 11... Nf6 12. Qe3 Nd5 13. Qd3 Nf6 14. h3 Qxd3 15. Bxd3 Bd5 16.
Be2 e6 17. c4 Be4 (17... Bxf3 $5 18. Bxf3 Be7 19. O-O O-O 20. d4 Rfd8 $11) 18.
d3 Bg6 19. Ne5 Nd7 $11) {White does not seem to have a good way to keep the
queens on the board, so he should probably play the endgame after} 11. g3 ({or
} 11. h4 {trying to gain some space on the kingside or develop the rook to h3.}
h5 $5 (11... Qxd3 $5 12. Bxd3 Bd5 {should be equal with the bishop on b2.}) 12.
Ng5 Qc8 13. O-O-O Bf5 14. Qg3 Qd7 15. Nf3 Ng4 16. Nd4 Bh7 $13 {Black will
complete his development soon and have a solid position.}) 11... Qxd3 12. Bxd3
Bd5 13. Be2 Rd8 $11 {This position is quite reliable for Black. He can
complete development with ...g6, ...Bg7 and white's dark-squared bishop will
be neutralized.} *

