1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 {This is another topical variation against the Caro
Kann these days. This modest-looking move was completely unknown in high-level
opening theory for many years. It leads to unexplored territories very early
in the game. The point is that White keeps the pawn on e4, unlike in most
other Caro-Kann variations, so the usual ...Bf5 is not possible here. In case
of the most principled continuation 3...dxe4 and the subsequent queen exchange,
the endgame is not as harmless as it might seem at first. White has found some
ideas to obtain a nagging advantage in the endgame based on the superfluous
move ...c6, which potentially weakens the dark squares on the queenside.
Therefore, Black needs to know what he is doing there. At this point Black has
many playable options, although I would recommend} dxe4 {as the most solid and
reliable option.} (3... Qc7 {is also a logical move, with the idea to take on
e4 and play ...e5 on the next move. White has many options now, but the most
interesting line is} 4. exd5 $5 ({I played} 4. Nc3 {myself as White in a blitz
game.} dxe4 5. dxe4 (5. Nxe4 Bg4 {This seems like a reliable alternative} ({to
} 5... Nf6 {which leads to a position that is similar to the main line of the
2 knights variation, only with d3 and Qc7 included:} 6. Qe2 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 {
It is not entirely clear whether these inclusions favor White or Black. In the
following game, White obtained a slightly better position after} Nd7 8. Bf4
Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qd5 10. Qf4 Nf6 11. Be2 g6 12. O-O Bg7 13. Rfe1 $14 {0-1 (76)
Perez Ponsa,F (2559)-Shimanov,A (2587) chess.com INT 2020}) 6. h3 Bh5 7. Qe2 e6
8. Bd2 Nd7 9. O-O-O Ngf6 {to me, this position looks perfectly sound and
playable for Black.}) 5... e5 6. Bc4 h6 (6... Nf6 {is dangerous because of} 7.
Ng5) 7. O-O Nf6 8. a4 {with a roughly balanced position that resembles the
Philidor defense now; playable for both sides.}) (4. g3 dxe4 5. dxe4 e5 6. Bg2
Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8. O-O Nd7 9. Qe1 $132 {1-0 (45) Andreikin,D (2726)-Shimanov,A 
(2593) Chess.com INT 2020}) 4... cxd5 5. c4 {attacking d5-square and trying to
exploit the position of Black queen in the future with the moves like Nc3-b5,
etc.} Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. a3 {Now 8.Nb5 is already on the agenda and White has a
slight initiative.} Nc6 {This is the safest.} ({In case of} 7... Be7 8. Nb5 Qd8
9. Bf4 {the c7-square is vulnerable.} O-O 10. Bc7 $5 (10. Nc7 Nh5) (10. Be2 Nc6
11. O-O a6 12. Nbd4 Bd7 13. b4 Re8 14. Nb3 $14 {0-1 (51) Caruana,F (2835)-Le,Q
(2709) chess24.com INT 2020}) 10... Qe8 11. Be5 Na6 12. Be2 {and as a result,
the knight is misplaced on a6, so I believe that White is slightly better in
this type of position.} Bd7 13. Nc3 Nb8 14. O-O Nc6 15. Bg3 Qd8 16. b4 $14) 8.
g3 a6 (8... Be7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O d4 {0-1 (44) Nepomniachtchi,I (2784)
-Fedoseev,V (2678) chess.com INT 2020} 11. Bf4 $1 Qd8 12. Na4 $14) 9. Bg2 $14 {
Black position is solid, but I prefer White's chances.}) ({Another approach is
} 3... Bg4 4. h3 Bh5 ({In case of} 4... Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Nd2 {White gets a
better version of the similar position from the 2 knights variation since the
knight is placed better on d2 than c3.} Nd7 7. g3 g6 8. Bg2 Bg7 9. O-O $14 {
1-0 (42) Alekseenko,K (2696)-Jobava,B (2603) Chess.com INT 2020}) 5. g4 (5. Be2
e6 6. Ne5 Bxe2 7. Qxe2 Bd6 8. Nf3 Nd7 $11 {1-0 (57) Carlsen,M (2863)-Svane,R 
(2613) Lichess.org INT 2020 1-0 (57) Carlsen,M (2863)-Svane, R (2613) Lichess.
org INT 2020}) 5... Bg6 6. Qe2 e6 {This is a complex position, though I prefer
White.} 7. h4 {The most logical move, trying to provoke weaknesses on the
kingside.} (7. Ne5 $6 {is actually a tactical mistake that was even played by
Magnus Carlsen.} Nd7 ({Black missed} 7... dxe4 $1 {when 8.dxe4 is not possible
due to 8...Qa5+, so White loses a pawn without enough compensation.}) 8. Nxg6
hxg6 9. exd5 cxd5 10. Bg2 Be7 11. c4 Nb6 12. Nc3 $14 {0-1 (32) Carlsen,M (2863)
-Svane,R (2613) Lichess.org INT 2020 0-1 (32) Carlsen,M (2863)-Svane,R (2613)
Lichess.org INT 2020}) (7. Nc3 {is also possible, leading into a complex
position after} d4 8. Nb1 h5 9. Rg1 hxg4 10. hxg4 $13 {etc.}) 7... h5 (7...
dxe4 8. dxe4 h5 9. g5 Na6 (9... Nd7 10. Nc3 (10. Bf4 $5) 10... Bb4 11. Bd2 Qc7
12. a3 Ba5 13. O-O-O O-O-O 14. Bg2 $14 {0-1 (54) Eljanov,P (2672)-Ezat,M (2401)
