[PlyCount "0"]

{In this lecture, I will mainly focus on the pawn structure arising in the
line 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4 Bf5. The idea of this approach is to
avoid repetitions since the other structures have been covered by the other
lecturers. On the board, you can see the most fundamental structure for the
entire variation. White has two main advantages in this structure: 1) space
advantage in the centre which is provided by the pawns on c4 and d4 2) the
control of the e-file, and more precisely the e5-square which is a perfect
outpost for the knight. Therefore, he avoids exchanges. In general, endgames
are pretty safe for Black because White's space advantage is not a very
important factor. By using his space advantage, White usually tries to develop
a kingside initiative. In order to "erase" this outpost, Black goes for the
advance ...c6-c5 which is his main idea in the position. After ...c6-c5 and
the exchange of the d4-pawn, we are going to transpose into Structure 2.
Another important idea in this pawn structure is the advance ...b7-b5. The
idea is to weaken the d5-square by provoking the advance c4-c5. This approach
will be dealt with in the section devoted to the light square strategy.}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Structure 2"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "6k1/pp3ppp/4p3/8/2P5/8/PP3PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "0"]

{This is another important structure that arises after the advance ...c6-c5.
Note that I examine multiple modifications of this pawn structure. For example,
very often the white h-pawn is on h5, instead of h2. Another important element
is the position of the king. In most of the examples, the white king will be
on the queenside. The most important factor for the evaluation of the position
is the control of the d-file. In general, Black should try to keep the queens
on the board. The reason is that Black's mobile central majority makes the
white king potentially weak. On the other hand, without queens on the board,
White can often create a distant passed pawn on the queenside. In the provided
model games, I speak a lot about the exchanges and the type of endgames we
want to achieve. Therefore, in order to avoid repetitions, I will not include
the same explanations here.}  *

