[SourceQuality "1"]

{In order to learn the best way of playing a given pawn structure, we should
know which are the worst scenarios. On the board, you can see a position that
can be potentially dangerous. In this situation, the h5-pawn prevents Black
from putting his kingside majority into motion. In order to keep drawing
chances, Black should keep at least one piece that can attack the h5-pawn.
Therefore, Black should avoid the exchange of the queens. An endgame with
knight versus bishop is lost for Black. In this position, Black played} 26...
Kb8 $6 {This move is not logical. The king goes away from the centre.} ({
The most precise move would have been} 26... Qd6 $1 {immediately trying to
exchange the knight.}) 27. Kc2 Qd6 28. Qd3 Qc5 $2 {This move is a serious
mistake. Now, the knight comes to the centre with a tempo.} ({The accurate} 
28... Qb6 $1 {would have allowed Black to maintain the balance.}) 29. Ne4 Qb6
30. b4 Ka7 31. Kb3 {Black has no useful ideas while White is gradually
improving his position.} Qc7 32. f3 Kb8 33. c5 Kc8 34. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4]
The knight is heading for the c4-square.} Qd7 $2 {This is the decisive mistake.
As we have already pointed out, Black shouldn't exchange the queens in this
position.} ({More tenacious would have been} 34... Qc6 35. Nc4 Bc7 {keeping
reasonable drawing chances.}) 35. Qxd7+ Kxd7 36. Kc4 Kc6 37. a4 b5+ 38. cxb6
Kxb6 39. Ne4 a5 40. b5 Bf4 {White's advantage is out of question. The knight
dominates Black's bishop. At the same time, the b5-pawn ties the black king.
In order to win, however, White needs to provoke further weaknesses on the
kingside. Therefore, his next task would be to provoke the advance ...f7-f6.
This can be done by transferring the knight to d6 or e5.} 41. Kd4 Kc7 42. Kd3
Kb6 43. Kc4 $1 {Of course, White doesn't need to rush. By giving the move to
his opponent, he provides him with a chance to make a mistake.} Kc7 44. Kd4 Bc1
45. Kd3 $1 Ba3 ({In a case of} 45... Bf4 {which could follow with} 46. g3 Be5
47. f4 {[%cal Ge4d2,Gd2c4] Followed by Nd2-c4. The bishop simply cannot keep
all the squares under control.}) 46. Nd2 Bb4 47. Nc4 Be1 48. Ne5 f6 49. Nc4 {
The first part of the plan has been completed. Now, White should go for
f3-f4-f5 in order to weaken the d5-square and fix the weak g7-pawn. In order
to mask his real intentions, Padevsky is making a couple of waiting moves.} Kd7
50. Ke3 Bb4 51. Kd4 Be1 52. Ke4 Kc7 53. Kf4 Kd7 54. Kg4 Kc7 55. Kf4 Kd7 56. Ke3
Bb4 57. Ke4 Be1 58. g4 Bb4 59. Kf4 Be1 60. Ke3 Bc3 61. Kd3 Be1 62. Ke4 Bc3 63.
f4 {Finally, White goes for his real idea.} Be1 64. f5 e5 65. Kd5 {With
Black's second weakness on g7, the win is simple.} Bb4 66. b6 $1 {Zugzwang.}
Be1 67. Nd6 Bf2 68. b7 Kc7 ({Or} 68... Ba7 69. Nc4) 69. Ke6 Ba7 70. Ne4 Kxb7
71. Kf7 Kc6 72. Kxg7 Kd5 73. Nxf6+ Kd4 74. Kxh6 e4 75. Nxe4 Kxe4 76. Kg6 {
Black resigns.} 1-0

