{[#] We have a typical endgame which is considered to be slightly inferior for
Black. Nevertheless, if you know the exact way of handling the position, you
can hold without too many problems. The most important principle is to keep
the piece that can attack the white kingside pawns. Therefore, Black's best
strategy would be to exchange the bishop for the white knight. In the game,
Dreev opted for another typical move which is wrong here.} 28... Nh7 $6 {
[%cal Gf7f5] Preparing the thematic ... f7-f5. Black, however, is not in time
to create sufficient counterplay.} ({Better would have been} 28... Bc7 $1 29.
Kc2 Bxe5 30. Bxe5 Nd7 {This is the right way to handle the position. My
analysis shows that in this structure, the knight can easily hold.} 31. Bc3 f5
$1 {This typical advance is the cornerstone of Black's counterplay. The next
step would be ...Kf7 followed by . ..g7-g6. We need to exchange as many pawns
as possible on the kingside. The idea is to potentially create a passed pawn.}
32. Kd3 Kf7 33. Ke3 ({In a case of} 33. gxf5 exf5 34. Kd4 g5 35. hxg6+ Kxg6 $11
{Black has enough counterplay thanks to the h-pawn.}) 33... g6 $1 34. gxf5 ({
Neglecting the kingside tension with} 34. Kf4 {also doesn't bring White any
advantage. For example, after} g5+ 35. Kg3 ({Another option would be} 35. Ke3 {
when after} e5 36. gxf5 Kf6 37. Ke4 Nc5+ 38. Kd5 Nd3 $11 {the draw is obvious.}
) 35... Nc5 36. b4 Nd3 {[%csl Rg3] White's king is cut off.}) 34... exf5 35.
hxg6+ Kxg6 $11 {As we already know, the h-pawn gives Black enough counterplay
for a draw.}) 29. Kc2 f5 30. Nd3 $6 {This move only wastes time.} ({Better
would have been to immediately start advancing the pawns -} 30. b4 Nf6 31. a4
fxg4 32. fxg4 Bc7 33. Nd3 Nd7 34. a5 Kf7 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gg6h5,Gg4h5,Gd7f6]
Preparing ...g7-g6 followed by ...gxh5 and ...Nf6. White, however, has} 35. Nf2
$1 {preparing to transfer the knight to e4.} Bd6 ({After} 35... g6 {[%cal
Gg6h5,Gg4h5,Gd7f6] White follows with} 36. Ne4 $18 {preventing ...Nf6.}) 36. c5
Be7 37. Kb3 $16 {[%cal Gb3c4,Gf2e4] Defending this position will be very
difficult for Black.}) 30... Ng5 $2 {Black shouldn't have allowed Nc5.} ({
More to the point would have been} 30... Be7 31. b4 fxg4 32. fxg4 Nf6 33. Nf2
Kf7 34. Kd3 e5 ({The typical} 34... g6 $2 {is bad here -} 35. Bxf6 Bxf6 36.
hxg6+ Kxg6 37. Ne4 {Once again, the e4-knight prevents Black's counterplay.}
Be7 38. c5 {Black should already reckon with Nd6 ideas. For example, after} h5
{, White is winning by means of} 39. gxh5+ Kxh5 40. Nd6 $18) 35. a4 Ke6 {
with a holdable position.}) 31. Nc5 b6 32. Nxa6 Nxf3 33. gxf5 exf5 34. b4 $6 ({
The simplest would have been} 34. c5 bxc5 35. Nxc5 $18 {White's connected
passed pawn will decide the game.}) 34... g6 35. hxg6 h5 36. Kd3 h4 37. Ke2 Ng5
38. Be5 h3 39. Kf1 $6 {After this slow move, Black saves the game.} ({White
should have played} 39. c5 bxc5 40. Nxc5 {with a probably winning position.})
39... Nf3 40. Bf4 Nh4 41. c5 bxc5 42. bxc5 1/2-1/2

