{In general, we have been all thaught that one shouldn't make pawn moves on
the wing where the opponent has superiority. In this pawn structure, however,
there is an important exception. I will try to briefly illustrate my point, by
providing a fragment which is taken from a blitz game of Riazantsev. In this
position, Black cannot put his kingside majority into motion because White's
active pieces will use the resulting weaknesses. The exchange of the rooks
will generally favour White because of the possibility to create a distant
passed pawn on the queenside. In such a case, while Black's pieces deal with
the passer, White will use his queen and knight to initiate play against the
king. Going for a knight endgame by exchanging all the major pieces is not a
good option. Since knight endgames are pretty similar to the pawn endgames,
the eventual distant passed pawn would give White an advantage. Black is
generally interested in the exchange of the knights. In the arising endgame
with major pieces, Black is doing fine if he keeps the d-file under control.
In the game, Riazantsev played} 25... b5 $1 {which is an idea that you should
remember. There two points behind this move: 1) it is preferable to exchange
pawns on the wing where we are weak 2) deflecting the c4-pawn gives Black the
important d5-square.} 26. cxb5 axb5 27. a4 bxa4 28. bxa4 Ra8 {[%cal Ga8a5,
Ge8a8,Gc7a7] Now, we can say that Black is even slightly better because the
a4-pawn is already a weakness. Black can put pressure on this pawn by means of
simple moves such as ...Ra5, ...Ra8 and ...Qa7. The remaining part of the game
is not that instructive (after all, this is a blitz game).} 0-1

