{This structure represents a very important structural modification. White
exchanges on f6 and Black recaptures with a pawn. Once again, I examine
different versions of the pawn structure. In most of the examples, White has a
pawn on h5 and a king on the queenside. In the analyzed model games, I prove
that the recapture ...gxf6 makes Black's structure even more flexible. For
example, gaining space on the kingside by means of ...f6-f5 doesn't weaken the
e6-pawn. Additionally, Black often puts pressure by using the g-file. In
positions with a white pawn on h5, the idea ...Rg8-Rg5 is really annoying
since the h5-pawn is a constant source of concern. As always, in each example,
I speak a lot about the exchanges. Overall, my conclusion is that in many
cases, this structure provides Black with decent winning chances.}  *

