{This position arose in one of my blitz games. Let's try to evaluate the
position. In this particular case, Black's doubled pawns are an advantage.
There are two reasons for that: 1) the possibility to put pressure along the
g-file 2) gaining space on the kingside by means of ...f6-f5 wouldn't provoke
weaknesses. Black has a classical winning plan in such positions. First of all,
he wants to exchange a pair of rooks in order to reduce White's counterplay.
The exchange of one of the white knights would be also favourable.
Additionally, Black tries to provoke g2-g3 by means of ...Rg8. Once, White has
committed to g2-g3, then Black can start preparing the ...f5-f4 break. Having
in mind all these factors, we can safely claim that White is the one who is
playing for a draw in this position.} 17... Rd8 $1 {[%csl Rh4] Exchanging a
pair of rooks.} 18. Rxd8+ Nxd8 {[%cal Gf6f5] Now, Black is ready to play ...
f6-f5, putting pressure on h4. Therefore, White's next move is obvious.} 19.
Nd6+ Bxd6 20. Rxd6 Ke7 21. Rd3 Nc6 {[%cal Gh8g8]} 22. g3 f5 {[%csl Rf2][%cal
Gh8g8,Gg8g4,Ge6e5,Ge7e6,Gf5f4,Gc6e5,Ge5g4] I have achieved What I wanted. The
idea is to provoke further weaknesses on the kingside. Black has two options
to achieve this goal: 1) the classical plan ...Rg8-g4 followed by ...e6-e5, ...
Ke6, and ...f5-f4 2) provoke the advance f2-f3 by means of ...Nc6-e5-g4} 23.
Rb3 b6 24. Rc3 Kd6 25. Rd3+ Kc7 26. c3 $6 {Maybe White was afraid of the
manoeuvre...Nb4-d5.} ({Better would have been to go for a rook endgame by
means of} 26. Nd4 {It is hard, however, to question moves played in a 3+0 game.
}) 26... Ne5 {[%cal Ge5g4] Going for the second plan.} 27. Rd1 Ng4 28. f3 Ne5 {
The mission is completed. Now, White will have problems to defend the
vulnerable kingside.} 29. Nd4 a6 {[%cal Gh8g8]} 30. Re1 $4 {A typical blunder
for a blitz game.} ({White's position, however, is already not so easy. For
example, after} 30. Rg1 {Black can play} Rg8 31. b3 h5 {[%cal Gf5f4] with the
idea of ...f5-f4. Now, the point of provoking f2-f3 becomes clear.}) 30... Nd3+
31. Kd2 Nxe1 32. Kxe1 Kd6 33. Kf2 Kd5 34. Ke3 b5 35. Kd3 Rg8 36. Ne2 e5 37. b3
Kc5 38. a3 a5 39. Ke3 Rg6 40. Kf2 a4 {GrigorGrigorov won by resignation} 0-1

