{Now, we shall take a look at a game of the big Caro-Kann expert and lecturer
in this camp Swapnil Dhopade. Here, White's position is even more difficult
because the h5-pawn is a constant source of concern. As we already know, the
first thing that Black should do in this position is exchanging a pair of
rooks. Therefore, Swapnil went for} 20... Rd8 $1 21. Rxd8+ Kxd8 22. Rd1+ Kc7 {
My personal choice would have been ...Ke7. In endgames with rooks, the king
should support the advance of his own pawns while the rook should fight
against the opponent's passed pawns.} 23. c4 Rg4 24. b3 f5 {[%cal Gf5f4] Black
is going for the most classical plan - ...f5-f4.} 25. Re1 Kd6 26. Kd2 e5 27.
Rh1 Ke6 {[%cal Gf5f4,Ge6f5] Of course, the Indian grandmaster does not rush.
He would like to carry out the advance ...f5-f4 under perfect circumstances.
The king will be transferred to the f5-square. At the same time, White has no
counterplay. His queenside majority is immobile.} 28. Re1 f6 29. Re3 f4 30.
gxf4 Rxf4 31. Ke2 Rf5 32. b4 Rf4 ({Another possibility would have been.} 32...
Rxh5) 33. b5 Na5 34. Ra3 b6 ({At this point, the simplest solution would have
been} 34... Re4+ 35. Kf1 Nxc4 36. Rxa7 Rf4 37. Ke2 Nd6 $17 {with an almost
decisive advantage.}) 35. Nd2 Kd6 36. Rd3+ Kc5 37. Rd7 Nxc4 38. Nxc4 Kxc4 39.
Rxa7 Rf5 40. a4 Rxh5 41. Rb7 Kc5 42. Rc7+ Kb4 43. Rb7 Kxa4 44. Rxb6 Rf5 45. Rb8
h5 46. b6 Kb5 47. Ke3 Ka6 48. f3 Rf4 49. Kf2 h4 50. Kg2 Kb5 51. Rb7 Ka5 52. Rb8
Ka6 53. Kf2 Ka5 54. Kg2 Kb5 55. Rb7 Kc5 56. Rb8 Kc6 57. Kf2 f5 58. Kg2 Rb4 59.
Rf8 f4 60. Kh3 Rb3 61. Kg4 Rxb6 62. Kxh4 Kd5 63. Kg4 Kd4 64. Ra8 Rg6+ 65. Kf5
Rg1 66. Ra4+ Ke3 67. Ra3+ Kf2 68. Kxe5 Kg3 69. Ke4 (69. Ra4 Rb1) 69... Re1+ 70.
Kd4 Kf2 71. Ra8 Kxf3 72. Kd3 Rd1+ 73. Kc2 Rd7 74. Rf8 Ke3 75. Re8+ Kf2 76. Rf8
f3 77. Rf6 Ke2 78. Re6+ Kf1 79. Rf6 f2 80. Rf8 Rg7 0-1

