{The next example features an interesting rook endgame. The game proves that
rook endgames are not dangerous for Black. In this position, Black should
decide how to deal with the pressure on g7. GM Svane plyaed the best move} 
23... Nf6 $1 {accepting the doubled pawns. Now, the rook endgame arises by
force after} 24. Nxf6 Bxf6 25. Bxf6 gxf6 {Once again, after exchanging a pair
of rooks, Black wants to proceed with ...Rg8 and ...f6-f5. As a rule, the
weakness of the h5-pawn is enough compensation for the doubled f-pawns.} 26.
Rh4 {In this pawn structure, the rook often enters the game via the fourth
rank. The main idea is to play Rf4 and counter ...f6-f5 with g2-g4. Of course,
Black is in time to prevent this threat.} Rxd1+ 27. Kxd1 Rg8 28. g3 Kd7 29. Rf4
f5 {[%cal Gg8g5] This is the safe construction for Black. The idea of ...Rg5
would always provide enough counterplay. Had the white pawn been on h2 
(instead of h5), Black would have had some practical problems to solve.} 30.
Ke2 Rg5 31. Rd4+ Kc7 32. Rc4+ Kd7 33. Rd4+ Kc7 {The draw is obvious.} 34. Rh4
Kd6 35. Kf3 Kc5 36. a4 b5 37. Ke3 e5 38. axb5 axb5 39. Rh1 Rg4 40. Ra1 Kd5 41.
Ra5 1/2-1/2

