{Now, I would like to show an instructive fragment from a recent game of mine.
Black is structurally better. His dream would be to put the king on e7,
exchange a pair of rooks and play f6-f5. In such a case, when the play is
going on two wings, the bishop would dominate the knight. Also, Black will
combine his pressure on h5 and g2. In this line of thoughts, I had the natural
desire to put my king on e7. The problem is that I failed to make this move
work tactically. It turns out that I have missed a typical tactical motif.} 
20... Kc7 $6 {After thinking for a long time, I settled for this dubious
continuation.} ({During the game, I rejected} 20... Ke7 $1 {due to} 21. Rhe1 {
[%cal Gd4f5] In my calculations, I was concerned about the idea of Nf5.
Nevertheless, it turns out that Black can just play} Rhd8 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Rg2,
Rh5][%cal Gd8d5,Ga8g8] when the h6-pawn cannot be really taken. For example,
after} 22. Nf5+ Kf8 23. Nxh6 $2 f5 {[%csl Rh6] The h6-knight is in danger.})
21. b4 {Now, White can force a draw.} Be7 22. Nb5+ Kc6 23. Nd4+ Kc7 24. Nb5+
Kc6 25. Nd4+ {and the draw is obvious.} 1/2-1/2

