{With the next example, I would like to briefly illustrate a very important
point. In positions with only major pieces on the board, despite the doubled
f-pawns. Black can safely castle on the short side. If the queen and rooks are
well placed, White will never create a mating attack. In this position, Predke
decided to attack by playing} 25. Rg7+ Kh8 26. Qe3 {Black, however, can easily
defend the kingside -} Qh5 27. Qg3 {[%cal Gg7h7] Setting the last trap. The
idea is Rh7+ followed by a mate on g7.} Qf5 28. Qe3 Qh5 29. Qf4 {This move
allows Black to exchange a pair of rooks, thus providing even more security to
the king.} Rd1+ 30. Rxd1 Kxg7 31. Rg1+ Kh7 32. Qg3 ({The alternative} 32. Qxf6
{is not dangerous either.} Rg8 33. Rd1 Rg4 34. b3 Qg6 {With a pretty much safe
endgame.}) 32... Qg6 33. Qh2 Qe4 34. Qg3 Qg6 35. Qh2 Qe4 36. Qg3 Qg6 37. Qh2
1/2-1/2

