{This is one of the most classical Caro-Kann structures. It arises when the
e5-knight is being exchanged. In my examples, the white king is usually on the
queenside and there is a White pawn on h5 (Black has a pawn on h6, instead of
h7 and his king is also on the queenside). White's space advantage can be
really dangerous in this position. White can create a lot of problems by
gaining space on the kingside. In some endgames, however, White's position
turns out to be overextended. As usual, one should know which pieces to
exchange and which pieces to keep on the board. The model games will make
clear several very important aspects: 1) endgames with dark-squared bishops
are very difficult for Black 2) Black can hold if his dark-squared bishop is
fighting against a knight (with or without rooks) 3) Endgames with major
pieces are generally OK for Black 4) Black can fight for an advantage with
queen and knight versus queen and dark-squared bishop (provided that all the
rooks are exchanged). The last point refers to the so-called light square
strategy which will be explained in great detail.}  *

