{We continue to deal with the fight of the minor pieces pieces. We shall take
a look at two examples which feature the duel between the knight and the
bishop. It turns out that without rooks on the board, the bishop could hold
the position without too many difficulties. Let's start with the recent game
Guseinov - Eljanov. Black's first task is to exchange the rooks. The reason is
that with rooks on the board, White can put pressure on the f7-pawn.} 20... Be7
21. Kf1 Rd8 22. Rxd8 Kxd8 {The first part of the plan has been completed. The
next step is to challenge White's space advantage on the kingside by means of .
..f7-f6.} 23. Ne4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg2g4,Gf4f5,Gf1e2,Ge2e3,Ge3f4,Gf5f6,Gg4g5]
White is planning to expand on the kingside in a way that we are already
familiar with - g2-g4 followed by f2-f4-f5-f6 and Ke2-e3-f4. Of course, this
scenario can be prevented with the simple} f6 {[%csl Re5]} 24. g4 {This move
doesn't create particular problems for Black.} fxe5 25. Ke2 Ke8 $1 {[%cal
Ge8f7,Gg7g6] Another key idea. Black is planning to proceed with ...Kf7
followed by ... g7-g6. Exchanging pawns on the kingside is the cornerstone of
Black's strategy.} 26. Kd3 Kf7 27. a4 g6 28. hxg6+ Kxg6 {It turns out that
White cannot make further progress in this position. Even Black was pushing
for a while. Objectively speaking, however, the position is a dead draw.} 29.
Nd2 Kg5 30. f3 Kf4 31. Ke2 b5 32. b3 bxa4 33. bxa4 Bc5 34. Ne4 Bb6 35. Nf6 Kg5
36. Ne4+ Kf4 37. Nf6 Kg5 38. Nh7+ Kf4 39. Nf6 1/2-1/2

