{Exactly the same endgame arose in the game Aleksandra Goryachkina - Olga
Girya. In this game, however, White managed to pose very difficult practical
problems to his opponent. After} 23. Ke2 f6 {Goryachkina played} 24. Nf1 {
creating the positional threat of taking on f6 followed by g2-g4.} Kd7 $6 {
White was hoping for this mistake.} ({Black should have played} 24... fxe5 $1
25. Kd3 Kd7 26. Ke4 Bf6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a6]} 27. Ne3 b5 28. Ng4 Kd6 {when it
is not clear how can White make any progress. Even if Black loses the e5-pawn,
the bishop can easily hold the position.}) 25. exf6 gxf6 26. g4 {[%cal Gf1e3,
Ge2f3,Gf3e4,Gf2f4] When playing Black, we should be aware of this dangerous
pawn structure. White wants to put his king on e4 and the knight on e3. The
move f2-f4 would be also a useful inclusion. In such a case, Black should
always reckon with the ideas f4-f5 and g4-g5. Girya went for the thematic} f5 {
which was answered by} 27. Ne3 $1 {This is the subtle point behind 24.Nf1! It
turns out that Black cannot keep his kingside structure intact.} fxg4 28. Nxg4
Bf8 29. Kd3 {[%cal Gd3e4,Gf2f4,Gf4f5]} b5 30. Ke4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] White is
planning to invade via the light squares after f2-f4-f5.} a5 31. f4 a4 32. f5
exf5+ 33. Kxf5 a3 34. b3 Kd6 35. Kg6 {White is already winning. Goryachkina
converted the advantage with confidence.} Kd5 36. Nxh6 b4 37. c4+ Kd4 38. Nf5+
Kc3 39. Kf7 Bc5 40. h6 Kb2 41. h7 Kxa2 42. h8=Q Kxb3 43. Nd4+ Bxd4 44. Qxd4 Ka2
45. Qd2+ Kb3 46. Qc1 1-0

