{Now, we shall take a look at a rook endgame. In general, the rook endgames
arising in this structure are not so dangerous for Black. Of course, some
precision is always required. As a key reference point, I would mention the
control of the d-file. Very often, we should be ready to sacrifice a pawn in
order to take the d-file under control. Let's take a look at the famous game
Sutovsky - Shankland. In this position, White played} 20. Rd3 {[%cal Gd3f3]
with the idea to put pressure on f7 by means of Rf3. The next few moves are
quite obvious -} Be7 21. Rf3 Rf8 22. Nh5 g6 23. Nf6 Bxf6 24. Rxf6 {[%csl Rh6]
[%cal Gh4h5] This is the position White was going for. He is mainly relying on
the activity of the rook. Additionally, White should decide how to deal with
the threat of h4-h5. Shankland took the correct decision.} Kd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7e7]
Of course, the priority should be the activation of the rook. Black is
planning to play ...Ke7 followed by ...Rd8.} ({A positional mistake would be} 
24... h5 $6 {since White can play} 25. f3 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg1f2] followed by Kf2
and g2-g4. In this case, White will either create a passed pawn on the h-file
or a weak black pawn on h5.}) 25. h5 gxh5 26. Rxh6 Ke7 27. Rxh5 Rd8 $1 {
The right approach to the position. The activity of the rook provides more
than enough compensation for the pawn.} 28. Rh4 Rd1+ 29. Kh2 Rd2 30. Rb4 b5 31.
f4 a5 32. Rb3 a4 $6 {This move allows White to activate his rook. Of course,
the position remains equal. After a number of mistakes, Shankland even lost
the game.} ({At this point, the simplest solution would have been} 32... f6 $1
{[%cal Gf6e5,Gf4e5,Ge7f7,Gf7g6,Gg6f5]} 33. exf6+ Kxf6 {with an obvious draw.})
33. Rb4 a3 34. bxa3 Rxa2 35. Rb3 Rc2 36. Kg3 Kf8 37. Kf3 c5 38. Ke4 c4 39. Rxb5
Rxc3 40. a4 Ra3 41. a5 c3 42. Kd3 Kg7 43. g4 Kg6 44. Kc2 Kh6 45. Rb7 Kg6 46.
Rb5 Kh6 47. Rb7 Kg6 48. Ra7 Ra4 49. a6 Rxf4 50. Ra8 Ra4 51. a7 Kg7 52. Kxc3 Ra1
53. g5 Kh7 54. Kc4 Ra2 55. Kc5 Ra6 56. Kb5 Ra1 57. Kb6 Rb1+ 58. Kc6 Ra1 59. Kd6
Kg7 60. Kd7 Ra2 61. g6 Kxg6 62. Rg8+ Kf5 63. a8=Q Rxa8 64. Rxa8 Kxe5 65. Ra5+
Ke4 66. Kd6 f5 67. Ra4+ 1-0

