{So far we have been mainly looking at endgames in which Black was fighting
for a draw. The moment has come to explain in which type of endgames Black can
play for a win. Very often the queen endgames can be unpleasant for White.
Since all the minor pieces are exchanged, White's space advantage is not
important. Having pawns on h4, e5 and c5, White is a bit overextended. Let's
take a look at a classical example. In this position, Black forced the
transition into a queen endgame by playing} 20... Nxc3+ 21. Qxc3 c5 $1 22.
Rxd8+ Qxd8 {Black wins a decisive tempo since the h4-pawn is under attack. Now,
the queen can invade White's camp.} 23. g3 Qd1+ 24. Qc1 Qe2 {Whis is
completely paralyzed. We can easily spot the tremendous difference in the
activity of the queens.} 25. Qf4 Qd1+ 26. Qc1 Qd3+ $1 27. Ka1 Qe2 {After this
beautiful triangle, Black is winning. White cannot protect his pawns by means
of Qf4 because of the mate.} 28. f4 Qf2 29. g4 Qxh4 {The rest is simple.
White's pawns are very weak.} 30. Qg1 b6 31. a3 Kc7 32. Qg2 Qd8 $1 {Taking the
d-file under control.} 33. Qe4 Qd1+ 34. Ka2 Qd4 35. Qc2 ({or} 35. Qa8 Qxc4+ 36.
Ka1 Qa6 $19) 35... Qxf4 36. Qa4 a5 {White resigns.} 0-1

