{One of Black's main weapons in Caro-Kann is the so-called light square
strategy. This strategy is very effective in the symmetrical pawn structure
with a space advantage for White. In order to use the light squares in an
effective way, Black would like to have queen and knight versus queen and
dark-squared bishop (all the rooks are exchanged). Let's take a look at the
classical game Ljubojevic - Karpov. In this position, Karpov went for} 24... c5
$1 {It is obvious that all the rooks are going to be exchanged on the d-file.
In such positions, Black has the following strategy: 1) put the queenside
pawns on dark squares in order to restrict the White's bishop 2) start playing
on the light squares by means of ...g7-g6 The move ...g7-g6 is indeed the
cornerstone of Black's strategy. The idea is to secure the f5-square for the
knight. If White answers with g3-g4, Black will play ...gxh5 followed by ...
Nf5. Alternatively, if White goes for hxg6, the Black can recapture with the
f-pawn and secure the f5-square for the knight by means of ...h6-h5.} 25. Rxd8+
Rxd8 26. Rd1 Rxd1+ 27. Qxd1 b6 28. Qd3 $6 {White doesn't feel the positional
danger.} ({More to the point would have been} 28. g4 {when Black can react
with the simple} Qb7 {with a decent counterplay on the light squares.} ({
Another possibility would be} 28... Qc6 {when after} 29. Qd6+ Qxd6 30. exd6 Ng8
{Black can easily hold the arising endgame. White should play energetically
since the d6-pawn is quite vulnerable.} 31. g5 Kc8 $1 32. b4 {the idea is to
free the d4-square for the bishop.} cxb4 33. Bd4 g6 $1 {This precise move
solves all the problems. The idea is that after} 34. gxh6 $6 Nxh6 35. Bg7 $2
gxh5 36. Bxh6 h4 $19 {Black is even winning.})) 28... g6 $1 {Finally, Black is
ready to execute this typical idea.} 29. hxg6 fxg6 {[%cal Gh6h5,Ge7f5]} 30. a3
a5 $1 {Karpov is not in a hurry. Before installing a knight on f5, he prevents
White from gaining space on the queenside.} 31. b3 ({If} 31. g4 {then Black
can play} h5 $1 {[%csl Gf5] weakening the f5-square.}) 31... h5 32. Qe4 Nf5 33.
Bf2 Qd7 34. a4 Kc7 $1 {Before activating his queen, Black tries to centralize
his king.} 35. Kc2 {From a static point of view, Black's advantage is obvious.
The queen and knight are a pretty strong tandem. Nevertheless, winning is not
simple at all since White has no obvious weaknesses. Additionally, after an
eventual exchange of the queens, the arising endgame is a draw. Black should
find a way to activate the queen and invade White's camp. Karpov played the
subtle} ({The attempt to demonstrate activity with} 35. Qa8 $2 {fails to} Qd3
$1 {When there is a knight around the king, there is no perpetual. For example,
after} 36. Qa7+ Kc8 37. Qa8+ Kd7 38. Qb7+ Ke8 39. Qb8+ Kf7 40. Qb7+ Ne7 $19 {
[%cal Gd3b3,Gd3f1] Black is winning.}) 35... Qd8 $1 {[%csl Ga8][%cal Gg6g5] A
very elegant decision. Black not only takes the a8-square under control but
also prepares the activation of the queen by means of ...g6-g5.} 36. Kc1 {
White has nothing better.} ({Preventing ...g6-g5 with} 36. Qf3 {runs into} Qd4
$1) ({After} 36. Qe2 {, Black takes the control of the light squares with} Qa8)
36... g5 $1 37. fxg5 Qxg5+ 38. Kc2 Ne7 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge7g6] Karpov
starts playing against the e5-pawn. The idea of his last move is ...Ng6.} 39.
Qh7 Kd7 40. Qe4 Qf5 41. Qd3+ Kc6 42. Qxf5 exf5 $1 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Ge7g6,Gc6d7,
Gd7e6] This is the right way to recapture. Black makes the e6-square available
for the king.} 43. Be3 Ng6 44. e6 Kd6 45. Bg5 Kxe6 46. Kd2 ({The immediate} 46.
Bd8 {runs into} f4 $1) 46... f4 $1 {A typical example of transformation of an
advantage. The h-pawn will decide the game.} 47. gxf4 h4 48. Ke3 h3 49. Kf3 Kf5
50. Kg3 Nxf4 51. Bd8 Ne2+ 52. Kxh3 Nd4 53. Bxb6 Nxb3 {Black is winning. The
rest is a matter of simple technique. Karpov converts his advantage in a
flawless way.} 54. Bd8 Ke4 55. Kg4 Kd3 56. Kf4 Kxc4 57. Ke4 Kc3 58. Bf6+ Kc2
59. Be5 c4 60. Ke3 c3 61. Bf6 Nc5 62. Ke2 Kb3 {White resigns.} 0-1

