{Now, we shall see how Riazantsev applied his light square strategy in a
slightly different structure. In this position, Riazantsev went for} 22... b5
$1 {A typical way of fighting for the light squares in this pawn structure.
The idea is to make use of the d5-square by provoking the advance c4-c5.} 23.
c5 Ne8 24. Kc2 Bf6 $1 {Once again, Black is more than happy to exchange his
bishop for the knight. In this way, he would enjoy complete domination on the
light squares.} 25. f4 Bxe5 26. fxe5 Nc7 {[%cal Gc7d5] The knight is finally
heading for the d5-square. After installing a knight on d5, Black can start
undermining White's space advantage by means of the advance ...f7-f6.} 27. g5
$6 {This advance seems to be a bit premature. As we are going to observe, the
h5-pawn can easily become a weakness.} Nd5 28. Bc1 hxg5 29. Bxg5 f6 30. Bd2 Kf7
{[%cal Gd8h8] Black's dream came true. Now, Riazantsev is ready to follow with
...Rh8.} 31. h6 Rh8 32. hxg7 Rxh1 33. Rxh1 f5 34. a4 bxa4 35. bxa4 Kxg7 $15 {
Black's advantage is obvious. The knight dominates the bishop. Additionally,
the protected passed pawn on f5 is a very important asset.} 0-1

