{Now, we shall take a look at a classical example featuring the light square
strategy. Playing on the light squares is one of the favourite approaches of
the big Caro-Kann expert GM Alexander Riazantsev. In this position, Black
seems to be under pressure since the g7-pawn is in danger. We know, however,
that in such positions the tandem queen + knight provides more than enough
counterplay. Of course, Black's first task is to exchange the rooks -} 22...
Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Rd8 24. Rxd8+ Qxd8 {It turns out that the pawn cannot be taken
because of the mate on d1.} 25. Kc2 Qf8 {Now, Black is in control. He can
start fighting for the light squares by means of ...g7-g6.} 26. Qe4 g6 $1 27.
Qf3 gxh5 28. Qxh5 Qg7 {[%cal Gg7h7,Gh7b1] The queen can occupy the diagonal
h7-b1.} 29. Kb3 Nc6 30. Qd1 {[%cal Gd1d6]} Qf8 {Preventing White from invading
the d6-square. Black will first transfer the knight to d7 (in order to better
protect the king). After that, the queen can be reactivated.} 31. Qd2 Nb8 32.
g4 Nd7 33. a4 Qg7 34. f3 Qg6 {Finally, Black managed to coordinate his pieces
sufficiently well. Now, he wants to get rid of the weak h6-pawn by means of ...
h6-h5.} 35. Qd6 h5 $1 {It becomes obvious why Riazantsev needed the knight on
d7. From this position, the knight not only covers the f8-square but also
protects the c5-pawn.} 36. Ba5 b6 37. gxh5 Qxh5 38. Qc6+ Kd8 39. Bc3 a5 $15 {
Black is already statically better. With a careful play, however, White can
hold the position. In the game, the Russian grandmaster failed to convert his
tiny edge.} 40. Qe4 Kc7 41. Qa8 Qf5 42. Qa7+ Kc8 43. Qa8+ Kc7 44. Qa7+ Kd8 45.
Qa8+ Ke7 46. Qc6 Qd3 47. Qb7 Qd1+ 48. Ka3 Qd3 49. Kb3 Kf8 50. Qc7 Ke7 51. Qb7
Kd8 52. Qc6 Qd1+ 53. Ka3 Qd3 1/2-1/2

