1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 {This recapture was
not so popular back in the 'classical' era of chess because of White's better
pawn structure. It has been widely considered as suspicious for Black because
White has a clear pawn majority on the queenside in the endgame. However,
nowadays strong engines have overruled this rather superficial verdict and
provided us with a better understanding of this interesting structure. Many
top-level players, including Magnus Carlsen, have used this system for Black,
showing that it is a good practical choice. This is especially true when one
plays for a win with black pieces. Strategically, this recapture allows Black
to strengthen his control over some important central squares, such as e5 or
even e4 later. The pawn mass of 4 pawns on the kingside also insulates the
black king from many attacking possibilities once Black castles kingside. The
recapture with the e-pawn allows him to quickly complete his development with.
..Bd6 and ...0-0 and then control the center with his pieces rather than the
pawns. It is also important to note that Black can sometimes even play for a
win in the endgame, especially if he is able to block the opponent's pawns
with the help of c6-b5-a4 pawn chain.} 6. Bc4 {One of the typical developing
moves.} ({The most popular developing scheme for White is} 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 {
These days, the main line goes} O-O 8. Ne2 Re8 9. Qc2 h5 $5 {and here White
has an option to castle both kingside and queenside. We will discuss this plan
in the game Duda-Carlsen.}) ({Slightly more passive, but also playable is} 6.
Nf3 Bd6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O {etc.}) 6... Bd6 {This relatively old game is
interesting because Alekhine's play was very strong and instructive, even by
modern standards. One of the important takeaways, as we will see, is that
exchanges are not always in the favor of the side with the better pawn
structure.} 7. Qe2+ {A popular move. White would like to force the queen trade
and play a nominally better endgame.} Be7 $5 {This seems to be losing a tempo,
but I prefer this move over the alternative 7...Qe7. White queen is actually
not doing much on e2 and we can later regain the lost tempo with ...0-0, ...
Re8 and ...Bd6.} ({The endgame after} 7... Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {is not too
dangerous for Black as he can mobilize his pieces quickly. That said, White
also plays it without any risk, so Alekhine's choice is more ambitious.}) 8.
Nf3 Bg4 $6 {This move is not bad, but I believe that it was better to complete
kingside development first with 8...0-0.} (8... O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Re1 {
Here, Black has two typical plans with the knight. I believe that it is a
matter of taste which one to prefer. 1)} Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gd7f8,Yf8g6] The
only downside of this move is that the bishop on e7 is pinned at the moment,
so White might have some tactic based on that.} ({and 2)} 10... Na6 $5 {
[%cal Ga6c7] White can compromise the pawn structure with} 11. Bxa6 (11. Bf4
Nc7 $11) 11... bxa6 $11 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gc8b7] but Black gets the bishop pair and
can create a lot of counterplay with moves like ...Qb6, ...c5 etc. I prefer
this way over 10...Nd7 because I do not think that Black should be too
concerned about this pawn structure given his piece activity. On the other
hand, 10...Nd7 can become practically difficult if White plays in the most
challenging way.}) {A very interesting option is} 11. Ng5 $5 {The alternatives
are not problematic for Black.} (11. d5 Nb6 12. dxc6 Nxc4 13. cxb7 (13. Qxc4
Be6 $44) 13... Bxb7 14. Qxc4 Rc8 $44) (11. Bf4 Nb6 (11... Nf8 12. Rad1 Be6 $11
{[%cal Gd8d7,Ga8d8]}) 12. Bb3 a5 13. a4 Nd5 $11 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc8e6]}) (11.
b3 Nf8 12. Ba3 Be6 $11) {with the idea} 11... fxg5 12. Bxg5 {Black has some
problems, but he can hold the balance with precise defense} Nf6 $5 ({In case of
} 12... Nb6 $6 {White gets a better endgame by force:} 13. Bxe7 Qxd4 ({or a
drawish Marshall-style endgame after} 13... Qd7 $5 14. Bb3 Nd5 15. Bxd5 Qxd5
$14) 14. Bf6 Rxe2 15. Bxd4 Rxe1+ 16. Rxe1 Be6 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. Re4 $14) (12...
Bxg5 $2 {leads to a lost endgame for Black because of the weak back rank} 13.
Qxe8+ Qxe8 14. Rxe8+ Nf8 15. d5) 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Qh5 Be6 15. Rxe6 fxe6 16.
Bxe6+ Kg7 17. Qf7+ (17. Bf5 $2 Rh8 18. Re1 Qe8 19. Qg4+ Kf8 $17) 17... Kh6 (
17... Kh8 18. Bf5 $18) 18. Bf5 {Fortunately, Black can defend the king with}
Rh8 {and eventually manages to survive.} 19. Re1 Qxd4 20. Bd3 Raf8 21. Qe6 (21.
Qxe7 Re8) 21... Bc5 22. Qh3+ Kg7 23. Qg3+ Kh6 24. Qh3+ $11 {In the view of
this complicated variation, I would personally prefer 10...Na6!? for Black.})
9. c3 Nd7 10. O-O ({White could, however, try to exploit the downside of the
early .. .Bg4 with} 10. h3 $5 Bh5 11. g4 $1 Bg6 12. Nh4 Nb6 13. Bb3 O-O 14.
Nxg6 hxg6 15. h4 $40 {[%cal Ge1f1,Ge2f3,Gh4h5] with the idea to keep the rook
on h1 for attack on the h-file, while he hides the king on f1 and puts the
queen on f3. This could lead to a dangerous attack for White.}) 10... Nb6 11.
Bb3 O-O {[%cal Gb6d5,Gf8e8,Ge7d6] Black has completed his development and has
a clear plan of improving his pieces: ...Nd5, ...Bd6, ...Re8, etc.} 12. Re1 {
This move is already not in the spirit of the position.} ({Once again, the
critical idea for White was} 12. h3 $5 Bd7 $1 {This is a little bit passive,
but we preserve our bishop from the exchange on g6.} ({hoping for} 12... Bh5
13. g4 Bg6 14. Nh4 {with a similar idea as in 10.h3!? variation.} Re8 15. Qf3
Bd6 16. Nxg6 (16. Nf5 $5) 16... hxg6 17. Kg2 $14 {[%cal Gf1h1,Gh3h4,Gh4h5]}) {
Black is pretty solid and safe after normal moves like:} 13. c4 (13. Bf4 Re8) (
13. Re1 Re8) 13... Re8 14. Be3 Bf8 $11) 12... Bd6 {White has several plans now:
...Qd7 followed by ...Ra(f)e8 or ...Bc7!?, ...Qd6 to prepare kingside attack.}
13. Bc2 {Another passive move, although White already hardly had strong
options.} ({In the event of the same idea as discussed before:} 13. h3 Bh5 14.
g4 Bg6 15. Nh4 {Black can already fight for the e-file with} Re8 16. Qxe8+ Qxe8
17. Rxe8+ Rxe8 {no time to take on g6 because of ...Re1+. After} 18. Bd2 Bd3 $1
$11 {Black takes control of the light squares and looks in a very good shape
thanks to the more active pieces.}) (13. c4 {is another standard option for
White, threatening the fork on c5. Black has many good options here.} Bb4 {
I prefer this move as it allows us the take control over the e-file} (13... c5
$5 14. dxc5 (14. d5 Nd7 $132 {gives Black a very nice blockade.}) 14... Bxc5
$11) (13... Bc7 $5 {is also very playable for Black.}) {after} 14. Rd1 Re8 15.
Qd3 g6 $132 {preparing...Bf5 with active play for Black.}) 13... Bh5 {[%cal
Gh5g6] An interesting move, trying to exchange light-squared bishops and
increase our control over the light squares this way.} ({Another logical move
is} 13... Re8 $5 14. Qd3 g6 15. Bh6 Bf5 16. Rxe8+ (16. Qd2 Nc4) 16... Qxe8 17.
Qd2 Nc4 {and Black gets easy piece play.} 18. Qc1 Qe6 19. b3 Na3 20. Bxf5 Qxf5
$11) 14. Qd3 {White was anxious to unpin and exchange some pieces.} Bg6 15. Qd1
{Black has many good moves now. Alekhine's choice was also logical} Bc7 {
[%cal Gd8d6]} (15... Re8 $11) (15... Qc7 $11) (15... Qd7 $11) 16. Bxg6 $6 {
Already a positional mistake because the arising 'cube' pawn structure is very
compact and potent for Black. White has no real plan now, as well.} ({
Relatively better was} 16. Nh4 Bxc2 17. Qxc2 Re8 (17... Qd6 18. g3 Rfe8 19. Bf4
Qd7 $11) 18. Rxe8+ Qxe8 19. Bd2 Nc4 20. Re1 Qd7 21. Bc1 Re8 22. Rxe8+ Qxe8 23.
g3 g6 24. b3 Nd6 25. c4 f5 $11 {[%cal Gd6e4]}) 16... hxg6 {[%csl Gf6,Gg6][%cal
Gg6g5,Gf6f5]} 17. Nd2 (17. Qd3 Qd7 $11) 17... f5 {Alekhine starts pushing his
pawns, which could become quite dangerous for White if Black could push them
to the fourth rank. Meanwhile, the white pawn majority on the queenside is
useless as White cannot play c4-d5 to create a passed pawn.} ({Another good
plan was} 17... Qd7 18. Ne4 Rfe8 $11) 18. Nf1 Qh4 19. Qf3 Rfe8 20. g3 Qh3 21.
Bf4 {A logical continuation of a previous couple of moves, especially
considering that White had a passive light-squared bishop and should, in
theory, exchange pieces. However, this allows Black to activate his knight
with a tempo.} (21. Bd2 $142) 21... Bxf4 22. Qxf4 Nd5 23. Qf3 Nf6 {[%csl Rf1,
Gf6][%cal Gf6e4,Gf6g4,Ye4g5] It becomes clear that Black has the better knight,
which is quite important in such positions.} 24. Re3 {White prepares to double
up on the e-file and make some exchanges.} ({In case of} 24. Qg2 Qh5 25. f3 {
Black continues to advance his pawns:} g5 $1 $15 {preparing ...g5-g4, etc.})
24... Rxe3 25. Nxe3 Re8 {Black controls the e-file.} 26. Rd1 Ne4 $15 {[%cal
Ge4g5] Black is already better here considering more active pieces and a
potentially vulnerable white king.} 27. Rd3 (27. Qg2 Qh5) 27... Ng5 28. Qg2 $2
{This is already losing.} ({White could still survive with} 28. Qd1 $142 $1 f4
$36 29. Ng2 {Practically, this looks very unpleasant for White, but he can
survive with precise defensive moves.} fxg3 ({or} 29... f3 30. Nf4 Qg4 31. h4
Re4 32. hxg5 Rxf4 33. Re3 Rf5 34. Re8+ Kh7 35. Re3 $11 {[%csl Rf3,Rg5]}) 30.
hxg3 Qf5 31. Nf4 f6 $11) 28... Qh5 {[%cal Gh5e2,Gg5f3] White cannot defend his
light squares now.} 29. Kf1 Nf3 30. h3 (30. h4 f4 $1) 30... f4 $1 {A nice
clearance combination.} 31. gxf4 Qb5 $1 $19 (31... Qf5 32. Rd1 Qxf4 $17) 32. c4
Qxc4 $3 $19 {The point. White loses material due to the checkmate on e1. A
masterpiece by Alekhine.} 33. Qxf3 Qxd3+ 34. Kg2 Qxd4 35. f5 gxf5 0-1

