1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. g3 $6 {An unusual,
although solid plan. The principled problem with this move is that White
weakens his light squares, which can become a real problem (as in Alekhine's
game, for example) should Black manage to exchange the light-squared bishops.
On the other hand, the upside of this development scheme is that it
significantly limits the influence of the bishop on d6.} Bd6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. Ne2
Bg4 {Not the only plan in the position, but a normal one, of course, as we pin
the opponent's knight and try to provoke the f2-f3 weakening.} 9. O-O Re8 10.
Re1 Na6 {In this case, this development route is better for the knight because
in case of ...Nd7-f8-g6, the knight would be useless on g6.} ({However, I
believe that it was more accurate to start with} 10... Qd7 $5 {[%csl Rh3][%cal
Gb8a6] in order to stop h2-h3 and only then continue with ...Na6-c7, etc.}) 11.
a3 ({The inclusion} 11. h3 Bh5 {would have been a better choice for White.})
11... Nc7 12. Qd3 Qd7 13. Bd2 ({In the event of} 13. c4 {we could go} h5 $5 {
to soften up opponent's kingside with ...h5-h4, etc. After} 14. Be3 Rad8 {
[%cal Gh5h4] the position remains approximately balanced, but I slightly
prefer Black as he seems to have an easier play.}) 13... Bf5 ({Better was} 
13... Rad8 {[%cal Gh7h5] to centralize the rooks first. In that case, White
could not have the d4-d5 break, as he did in the game.}) 14. Qb3 Ne6 $6 {
[%cal Ge6g5] Salgado went for the kingside attack with ...Ne6-g5 immediately,
but abandoned the d5-square, which could have provided White with counterplay.}
({Better was} 14... b5 15. c4 Be4 $11 {keeping control of the central squares.
As mentioned earlier, this exchange is favorable for Black as it weakens light
squares around white king.}) (14... Rab8 {was also better than the game move.})
15. Be3 $2 {Too passive.} ({White had to play} 15. d5 $1 cxd5 16. Qxd5 {
with good counterplay. For example:} (16. Bxd5 Nc5) 16... Bxc2 17. Rac1 Ba4 18.
Qxb7 Qxb7 19. Bxb7 Rab8 20. Bc6 Bxc6 21. Rxc6 $14) 15... Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rf3,Rg1,
Rg2,Gg5,Rh3] Black has achieved the ideal attacking position. There are many
threats on the light squares.} 16. Nf4 $2 {This is bad as it allows Black to
dominate on the light squares.} (16. Bxg5 fxg5 $15 {would not solve White's
problems because Black would then have a clear long-term positional advantage
with the bishop pair and mobile kingside pawn majority.}) ({He had to play} 16.
d5 c5 17. Nc3 {stopping ...Be4 and trying to keep control of the light squares.
}) 16... Be4 17. Bxe4 $2 {Too cooperative.} (17. Bd2 $142 Rad8 $17) 17... Rxe4
$19 {Black is completely winning now.} 18. Kg2 Rae8 ({Even faster was} 18...
Bxf4 $1 19. Bxf4 Qh3+ 20. Kh1 Rxf4 $1 21. gxf4 Nf3 $19) 19. Rf1 Bxf4 20. Bxf4
Qh3+ 21. Kh1 Rxf4 $1 (21... Rxf4 $1 22. gxf4 Nf3 $19) 0-1

