1. e4 {[%mdl 4256]} c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6
7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Re8+ 9. Be3 {This is not the main line, but it is quite
possible, of course. White plans to quickly castle queenside, so he does not
want to waste a tempo on Ne2,} ({which is the main line} 9. Ne2 h5 {as we will
see in Duda-Carlsen.}) 9... h5 $5 {This move looks suspicious, but it has
proved to be the best way to defend the pawn. It slows down White's kingside
attack considerably since g2-g4 is difficult to prepare. White has a difficult
time exploiting the weakness of this pawn. In fact, it often moves forward to
h4, helping Black gain even more space on that side of the board.} 10. O-O-O {
I find this move to be premature in the view of the following answer:} Qa5 $1 {
[%csl Ra2]} 11. Kb1 Be6 {[%csl Ra2] Now White needs to create a weakness in
his queenside structure.} 12. c4 (12. a3 {[%csl Ra2,Rb3][%cal Ge6a2] leaves
too many weaknesses on the light squares and Black has an easy way to exploit
them:} Nd7 13. Ne2 b5 $132 {[%cal Gd7b6]}) 12... Na6 {This is the important
difference compared to the main line in which usually Ne2 and Nd7 are inserted
for White and Black, respectively. The weakness of b4-square provides Black
with a nice initiative right out of the opening.} ({However, in retrospect
even stronger was} 12... b5 $1 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Ge6a2]} 13. d5 cxd5 14. cxd5 (
14. cxb5 $2 d4) 14... Bg4 15. Ne2 Na6 $40 {[%cal Ga6b4]}) 13. Bd2 $2 {My
opponent thought for a long time here and made a worse choice.} ({The critical
move was} 13. a3 $1 {when Black has a dangerous piece sacrifice} Bxa3 $1 (13...
b5 $6 14. c5) 14. bxa3 Qxa3 {[%cal Ga6b4] exposing white king. However, White
has enough defensive resources to hold the balance with correct play.} 15. Bd2
(15. Bc1 Qb4+ 16. Qb2 (16. Bb2 b5 $40) 16... b5 $1 17. c5 (17. Qxb4 $6 Nxb4 {
[%cal Gb4d3,Ge6f5]}) (17. cxb5 Qd6 $40 {[%cal Ga8b8,Ga6b4]}) 17... Ba2+ $1 {
[%cal Gb4a4]} (17... Qa4 18. Ne2 Nb4 19. Nc3) 18. Ka1 (18. Kxa2 Qa4+) 18... Bb3
19. Bc2 Qa5+ (19... Bd5 20. Nf3 Qa5+ 21. Kb1 Re2 22. Rd2 Rae8 $44) 20. Kb1
Bxc2+ 21. Qxc2 b4 22. Bb2 Nc7 23. Ne2 Nd5 24. Rhe1 Reb8 $44 {[%csl Rb1]}) ({
White can also force a draw with} 15. Qb2 Qa4 16. Qc2 (16. Bc2 Qxc4 $44) 16...
Qb4+ 17. Qb2 $11 {which might be the best practical decision in such a
dangerous position where Black has a lot of play for the piece.}) 15... Nb4 (
15... b5 16. Qc3 Qxc3 17. Bxc3 bxc4 18. Be4 (18. Bc2 Nc7 $44) 18... Bg4 19. Re1
Rxe4 20. Rxe4 Bf5 21. f3 Re8 22. Kc1 Bxe4 23. fxe4 Rxe4 $44) 16. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 17.
Qb2 (17. Kc1 b5) 17... Qa4 18. Ne2 (18. Qc2 Qb4+ $11) (18. Nf3 Bxc4) 18... Bxc4
19. Nc3 Qa6 20. Bxc4 Qxc4 21. Rd2 Rad8 22. Rhd1 b5 $44 {[%csl Ga7,Gb5,Gc6]})
13... Nb4 14. Qb3 $2 ({Black is at least slightly better with the bishop pair
after} 14. Bxb4 Bxb4 {[%csl Gb4,Ge6]} 15. a3 Bf8 $15 {[%csl Ge6,Gf8][%cal
Gb7b5] but this was probably a better choice than the game continuation.})
14... b5 $1 15. Bxb4 ({It is important that} 15. a3 $2 {is not working for
White because of} bxc4 16. Bxc4 (16. axb4 Qb5 $19) 16... Qf5+ $19 {[%csl Rb1]
[%cal Gf5b1]} 17. Ka1 Nc2+ 18. Ka2 Nxd4) 15... Bxb4 16. Qc2 bxc4 17. Bxc4 {
Black is clearly better now as his rooks will control important files and
white king is much weaker than the black one. White may have some hopes of
keeping the position solid on the light squares.} Bxc4 (17... Rab8 $142 $17)
18. Qxc4 Rab8 19. Nf3 Ba3 20. b3 Qf5+ {Among several good possibilities, Black
prepares a favorable transformation into the endgame where he will secure the
penetration to the second rank. This seems like the simplest practical
solution.} 21. Qd3 Qxd3+ (21... Qd5 $17) 22. Rxd3 Re2 23. Rd2 Rbe8 {also ...
g5-g4 is on the cards. The endgame is nearly lost for White since the knight
is inferior to the bishop in such positions.} 24. Rhd1 (24. Rf1 g5 $17) 24...
Bb4 25. Rxe2 Rxe2 26. Rc1 Rxf2 27. Rc2 {Trying to exchange the rooks.} Rxc2 ({
A better conversion would have been} 27... Rf1+ $1 28. Kb2 g5 $1 29. Rxc6 (29.
a3 Be7) 29... g4 30. Nh4 f5 $19) 28. Kxc2 Kf8 29. Kd3 Ke7 30. Kc4 a5 31. d5 {
White is trying to increase his drawing chances by exchanging the pawns and
activating the king.} c5 $1 {We do not want to exchange pawns. The plan is to
go ...Kd6 to attack the d5-pawn and then just push the kingside pawns.} (31...
cxd5+ 32. Kxd5 {[%csl Gd5]}) 32. Ng1 $2 ({The last hope for White was} 32. h3
$1 Kd6 33. g4 {blocking black pawns.} hxg4 34. hxg4 g6 35. Ng1 $17) 32... Kd6
33. Ne2 g6 34. Nf4 h4 {Now the pawns are unstoppable. White has no counterplay
at all. His pawns are blocked.} 35. Nd3 f5 36. h3 g5 $19 37. Nb2 f4 38. Nd3 f5
39. a4 Ba3 {Zugzwang!} 40. Kb5 (40. Ne1 g4 $19) (40. Nf2 Bc1 41. Nd3 Be3 $19 {
the bishop has been improved from b4 to e3 and Black is winning.}) 40... Bb4
41. Kc4 Ba3 42. Kb5 Kxd5 43. Kxa5 Kd4 44. Nxf4 (44. Kb5 Kxd3 45. a5 c4 $1 {
An important move to stop the a-pawn.} 46. bxc4 Kd4 47. a6 Bc5 $19) (44. Ne1
Bb4+) (44. Nf2 c4 45. bxc4 Kxc4 46. Ka6 Bc5 47. Nd1 g4 $19) 44... gxf4 45. Kb5
Bb4 46. a5 Bxa5 47. Kxa5 c4 0-1

