{[%evp 0,95,27,12,69,69,61,25,43,44,40,42,42,-24,-1,-8,-20,-22,-13,2,30,-7,38,
13,5,-8,-19,-10,11,16,34,33,37,18,32,16,14,17,35,34,36,34,45,42,34,37,11,0,0,
-3,-16,-28,-40,-30,-9,-13,0,-13,-12,6,-17,-25,-40,-31,-25,-33,-31,-59,-37,-53,
-51,-82,-14,-17,-11,-25,-25,-64,-79,-92,-86,-96,-91,-94,-92,-84,-70,-73,-71,
-72,-66,-87,-68,-116,-100,-99,-96,-109] This game is a good example of how to
outplay your opponent in the endgame in this structure.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3.
Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. g3 Bd6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. Ne2 Re8 9. O-O {
This is the same as in the game of Ivan Salgado. Now, I continued differently
with} Nd7 $5 ({Salgado's} 9... Bg4 {is probably the best.}) 10. Bf4 {In the
principle, this is a good exchange for White.} Nf8 11. Re1 {There were some
inaccuracies in the opening from both players as this was a blitz game. Anyway,
we are mostly interested to see the typical endgame that will arise soon.} Bg4
(11... Bxf4 $5 12. Nxf4 Rxe1+ 13. Qxe1 Qxd4 14. Qe8 (14. Rd1 Qe5) 14... Rb8 15.
Re1 Qd6 $15) 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. c3 Qe7 $6 (13... Ng6 $142) 14. Qd2 Ng6 (14...
Bxe2 $6 15. Bf1 $14) 15. Nf4 Qd6 {A very interesting strategic moment - should
White exchange the knights or not?} 16. Nxg6 {I believe that this is a small
mistake. As we have seen in Alekhine's game, the arising pawn structure is
deceiving - it seems bad for Black, but it holds a lot of dynamic potentials
as the pawns can be pushed forward without weakening the king's position.} ({
White should have played instead} 16. Nd3 $11 {as the knight is placed well in
the center, while black knight is rather passive on g6 in this structure, as
we mentioned in the previous game.}) 16... hxg6 {[#] This is an important
position for understanding typical ideas in the late middlegame/endgame in
this structure. On the surface, it might seem like White is slightly better
due to his pawn majority, however, the position is roughly equal, but perhaps
even easier to play for Black. The point is that Black has a simple plan of
preventing White's pawn expansion with ...Be6, ...a5-a4 on the queenside,
while starting to advance his kingside pawns: ...g5, ...g6, later ...f5-f4,
etc.} 17. h3 ({White should probably exchange pieces} 17. Rxe8+ Rxe8 18. Re1
$11) 17... Be6 18. Re3 (18. h4 $5 {stopping ...g5.}) 18... a5 (18... g5 $5 {
was better immediately, but this being a quick-control game, it was not easy
to play the most accurate moves due to lack of time.}) 19. Rae1 Rad8 20. Qc2
Kf8 21. Qa4 Ra8 22. a3 g5 {Black is already slightly better, in my view, as
white pawns have been stopped and there is a strong plan for Black on the
kingside.} 23. Qc2 g6 24. Qe2 Kg7 $1 {preparing ...Rh8 to attack the weak
h3-pawn.} 25. Qc2 Rh8 $36 26. g4 {This seriously weakening move has to be
played, so Black achieves an important positional victory.} Rhe8 27. Qe2 b5 28.
Be4 Bc4 29. Qf3 Rac8 30. Bc2 Bd5 {As the game progresses, we can see how it is
possible for Black to slowly outplay his opponent in what seems to be a simple
equal endgame that is typical for this variation.} 31. Be4 Bc4 32. Bc2 Rxe3 33.
Rxe3 (33. Qxe3 $142) 33... b4 {An important breakthrough to open some files
for heavy pieces and create the second weaknesses.} 34. axb4 axb4 35. Qd1 (35.
Be4 Ra8 {and white king becomes exposed.}) 35... Ra8 36. b3 {This weakens the
d4-pawn,} ({but} 36. Bb3 {does not help either because after} Bxb3 37. Qxb3
Ra1+ 38. Kg2 c5 $40 {[%csl Rg2] white king is even more exposed.}) 36... Be6
37. c4 Rd8 38. Be4 $2 ({A more stubborn defense was} 38. Qd2 Qxd4 39. Qxb4 c5
$17 {[%csl Rb3,Rc4,Gc5] but it is clear that Black is better anyway.}) 38... f5
$1 {The pawns start moving.} 39. Bf3 (39. gxf5 gxf5 $17) 39... Qxd4 40. Qxd4+
Rxd4 $19 {This endgame is winning for Black because White has many weak pawns:
b3, h3, g4.} 41. Bxc6 (41. gxf5 gxf5 42. Bxc6 Kf6 $19 {[%csl Rb3,Rc4][%cal
Gf5f4]}) 41... fxg4 (41... Kf6 $19) 42. hxg4 Rxg4+ 43. Kf1 Rd4 44. Ke2 Kf6 45.
