{[%evp 0,94,19,38,72,60,64,34,33,20,28,35,31,39,42,0,-4,-5,16,-3,26,33,48,40,
45,52,64,51,51,57,38,41,41,26,48,46,32,31,12,19,11,-7,25,0,0,0,0,-4,0,-26,0,
-52,-35,-40,-29,-50,-42,-40,-40,-49,-36,-54,-48,-56,-80,-92,-92,-77,-94,-51,
-93,-56,-96,-110,-108,-145,-137,-158,-162,-174,-168,-156,-136,-176,-171,-200,
-189,-205,-251,-303,-277,-525,-599,-726,-863,-29987,-29988]} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5
3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. d4 Bd6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. c4 {
Natural opening strategy by White. He asserts his pawn advantage in the center,
potentially preparing d4-d5 to create a passed pawn.} Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f8] In
this particular position, the plan with the knight transfer to g6 via f8 makes
the most sense for Black.} 10. Bd3 {Nepomniachtchi improved his bishop to a
more active diagonal, also preventing Black from putting his bishop on f5. A
sensible plan even if it loses a tempo.} ({After} 10. Be3 Nf8 {[%cal Gc8g4]
Black could develop the bishop to either f5 or g4.}) 10... Nf8 11. h3 {
Continuing to limit black bishop, which now has only two relatively passive
squares, d7 and e6, available.} Ng6 12. Qc2 Qa5 $5 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Ga5h5] An
impressive idea, preparing to swing the queen over to h5 and threaten ...Bxh3
that way.} ({The simplest continuation would have been} 12... Be6 {preparing ..
.Qd7 with a dangerous threat to sacrifice a piece on h3 for attack. White
would have to prevent that with} 13. Bf5 {and after} Qd7 14. Bxe6 Rxe6 $11 {
[%cal Ga8e8] Black is obviously completely fine as he controls the e-file, but
this is also the kind of position that White does not mind as there is no risk
involved, especially if he exchanges all rooks.}) 13. c5 {White should not
allow 13...Qh5, but this is a structural concession that Carlsen was trying to
provoke with his previous move. As we will see, the d5 square will play a key
role in the remainder of the game.} (13. Bd2 $6 Qh5 $36) 13... Bb8 {[%cal
Ga5c7] The bishop is still the best on this diagonal, sometimes in connection
with ...Qc7.} 14. Bd2 Qd8 (14... Qc7 {would be very similar to the game after}
15. Rfe1 Be6 16. Re3 $11) 15. Rfe1 Be6 16. Bc4 Nf8 {Carlsen retreated the
knight in order to recapture ...Nxe6 in case of Bxe6. That way, the knight
would exert pressure on the d4 pawn. It is essential to keep the d4-d4 break
under control and Black will be fine.} ({Another reasonable option was} 16...
Bxc4 17. Qxc4 Rxe1+ 18. Rxe1 Bc7 $11 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ga8d8]}) 17. Rad1 Bc7 18. Qb3
Bxc4 19. Qxc4 Qd7 20. b4 {White would like to push a4-b5, etc. to create some
play on the queenside.} Ng6 {Carlsen changes the plan; instead of going to e6,
he takes a different route as he would like to plant his knight on a strong
d5-outpost. In such maneuvering positions, losing a tempo or two for this
purpose is not a problem.} 21. a4 Ne7 22. b5 Nd5 $11 {Black has fulfilled his
plan and now the knight dominates in the center. Nepomniachtchi tried to
complicate matters with} 23. bxc6 bxc6 24. Qa6 {as he puts pressure on the
queenside pawns. But Carlsen's strong reply} g5 $1 $40 {[%cal Gh7h5] created
much more serious threats. Black plans to simply attack with ...h5, ... g4 and
even ...Kg7, ...Rh8 at some point. White position is already quite problematic.
} 25. Nh2 {Trying to bring the knight to f1 and e3 to exchange the powerful
d5-knight.} (25. Rb1 h5) 25... Bxh2+ $1 $17 {The best move. Carlsen transforms
his advantage into a position with a strong knight versus bad bishop. Black
controls everything and is virtually up a pawn since d4-pawn is firmly blocked.
} 26. Kxh2 Kg7 {[%csl Rd2,Gd5] Black is in no hurry. He can slowly improve his
position and wait for the opponent's mistake in a passive position.} 27. Kg1
Rxe1+ 28. Rxe1 Rb8 {Logically, Black takes the control of the open file.
Meanwhile, White has no impact on the e-file.} 29. Qd3 Rb2 30. a5 h6 {Carlsen
continues the waiting strategy as White hardly has a useful move to make.} 31.
Bc1 Ra2 32. Bd2 Qb7 {The queen joins the rook in the attack on the b-file. The
position is already strategically winning for Black, so Nepomniachtchi tried
the last desperate attempt} 33. Re8 Qb2 34. Be1 Nf4 35. Qa6 Qxd4 36. Qc8 Ng6 {
This move defends everything.} 37. Qxc6 (37. Rg8+ Kh7 38. Qe8 Qc4 $19) 37...
Ra1 38. Qe4 (38. Kh2 Ne5) 38... Qxc5 $19 39. Kh2 h5 40. Qe3 Qc6 41. Bc3 Ra4 42.
f3 Ra2 43. Kh1 Rc2 44. Be1 Qb5 45. Bg3 h4 46. Bh2 Qb1+ 47. Bg1 Qf1 0-1

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Lecture Introduction, Caro-Kann Defence"]
[Black "Advanced Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Swapnil Dhopade"]
[Variant "illegal"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "8/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/8 b - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "0"]
[EventDate "2020.11.27"]

{Hello Friends! This is GM Swapnil Dhopade from India and in this lecture, we
are going to examine typical structures resulting from the Advance Variation
of the Caro-Kann Defence. I have been playing the Caro-Kann Defence since the
start of my career as a chess player, right until I attained my Grandmaster
title. As a staunch adherent of the Caro-Kann Defence, I have tested
practically every line with the black pieces and dealt with various white
options from the black pieces. With all honesty, I must confess that the
Advanced Variation was the toughest one to understand and play against. Many
structures are arising from this variation, and the play in all of them is
normally quite complex. The engine is of limited help in this variation for
players who have little experience in this Caro-Kann Defence. The engine might
show huge plus for white in some strategical position, while in fact, it is
just better for black. Therefore, it makes sense to grasp the essence of any
variation, study the structures arising in that variation. When we say study
the Pawn Structure, we mean we need to know the typical plans for both the
sides, intricate manoeuvrings, essential pawn breaks, etc. When we have an
excellent knowledge of the above, we can play confidently and handle unknown
situations much better. So let us study unique structures in the Advance
Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence. I hope, after this lecture, you will face
the Advance variation with confidence and precision.}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to -"]
[Black "Various Pawn Structures"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Swapnil Dhopade"]
[Variant "illegal"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "8/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/8 b - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "0"]
[EventDate "2020.11.27"]

{[%cal Gc6c5] There are numerous structures in the Advance variation and we
will take a look at them one by one. The main set structures in the Advance
Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence arises when Black breaks with the typical
c6-c5. Here is the list of the structures that we are going to study:-
Structure 1 - Black breaks with c6-c5. Then either - a. white captures on c5
with dc5 or b. Black captures on d4 with ...cd4 and white recapture with a
piece. In both cases, we get the same structure. Structure 2 - Black breaks
with c6-c5 and White responds with c2-c3. Then Black captures on d4 with ...
cd4 and white recapture with the pawn cd4 (If white recapture with the piece
then we transpose to structure 1). Structure 3 - Black breaks with c6-c5 and
White responds with c2-c3. The Black advances on the queenside with c5-c4.
Structure 4 - Black breaks with c7-c5 and white breaks with c2-c4. Structure 5
- White breaks with c2-c4 before black gets a chance to break with c6-c5.
Structure 6 - White advances on the kingside with h2-h4 and black responds
with h7-h5. Structure 7 - White advances on the Kingside with h2-h4 and black
responds with h7-h6. Structure 8 - White advances on the Kingside with g2-g4
before playing h2-h4. [#]}  *

