{This structure occurs after Black breaks with c6-c5. Then either - a. white
takes on c5 with dc5 or b. Black captures on d4 with ...cd4 and white
recapture with a piece. In both instances, we get the same structure.
Important points to remember in this structure:- 1. White usually has the d4
square under his control and he will try to place a piece on this square.
Black can try to challenge white’s control of this square by putting one
knight on c6 and the other knight on f5. Other ways to challenge the d4 square
is to bring out the bishop to c5 or the Queen to b6.2. In this structure white
pawn on d4 is missing. Hence, White’s e5 pawn lacks its traditional support.
This makes black’s f7-f6 break very desirable and stronger.}  *

