1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. c3 cxd4 8. Nxd4
Nge7 {Black is not afraid to exchange the light square bishop for the
important knight on d4. As we already know the white knight on d4 is a very
important piece in this position. Also, Black's Knight reaches its optimal
position on f5.} 9. Nxf5 Nxf5 {[%csl Gf5] The black knight is usually well
placed on f5.} 10. Bd3 g6 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8g7] A nice move. Black not
only supports the knight on f5 but also prepares to fianchetto his Bishop to
g7.} 11. Qe2 Bg7 12. f4 O-O {[%cal Gf7f6] Black has completed his development
and is now all set to break with f7-f6.} 13. Nd2 {[#]} f6 $1 {this is a
desirable break for black in this structure. In the absence of the pawn on d4,
the e5 pawn can be easily targeted with the f7-f6 pawn break.} 14. exf6 Qxf6 {
[%cal Gg7a1] Now we can see that with the disappearance of the pawn on e5, the
Bishop on g7 enjoys good control on the a1-h8 diagonal. Black's pawn structure
is slightly weaker compared to white's because of more number of pawn islands 
(2 vs. 3). But, Black's pieces are well placed. So Black's Pawn structure is
not big of an issue here.} 15. Nf3 Rae8 {[%csl Rc1,Gc6,Ge8,Gf5,Gf6,Gf8,Gg7] [#]
all the black pieces are actively placed and the position is balanced for both
sides. Another important thing to note is that the White Bishop on c1 is very
limited because of his pawn on f4.} 16. Bb5 {a typical idea for white,
fighting for the e5 square.} Qd8 {[%cal Gd8b6]} 17. Kh1 Qb6 18. Ba4 Re7 19. Re1
Kh8 20. Bb3 Na5 21. Bc2 Nc6 22. Bb3 Na5 23. Bc2 Nc6 24. Bb3 1/2-1/2

