{[%cal Gc7c5,Gc2c3,Rc5d4,Rc3d4] This structure arises after Black breaks with
c6-c5 and White responds with c2-c3. Then Black captures on d4 with ...cd4 and
white recapture with the pawn cd4 (If white recapture with the piece then we
transpose to structure 1). Important points to remember in this structure:- 1.
The open c-file is a major point to remember. Black will either try to
dominate and infiltrate via the c-file or he should try to exchange the major
pieces on c-file, simplifying the position and thus reducing white's chances
of an attack on the kingside. So, c-file is a major source of counterplay for
black. 2. Usually, Black's one knight stands on c6 while the g8 knight has two
routes:- a) The g8 knight goes to b6 via g8-e7-c8-b6 and helps create a play
on the queenside. Or b) The g8 knight goes to f5 via g8-e7-f5 after Black
moves his Bishop from f5 to e4 or g4. With the knight on f5 black can put
pressure on the d4 pawn. Black can also consider exchanging his light square
bishop for the knight on f3 with Be4 or Bg4, thus weakening the d4 point.}  *

