1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. c3 cxd4 8. cxd4
Nge7 9. a3 Nc8 $5 {this is an interesting route for the black knight to be
remembered in this structure. The Black knight goes to the queenside directly.
Black also prepares to develop his dark square Bishop next.} 10. Nbd2 (10. Bg5
$142 Be7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nc3 $10) 10... Be7 11. b3 a5 $1 {[%cal Gc8a7] black
gains space on the queenside and hopes to bring his knight to b5. From the b5
square the Knight can aim to enter the c3 square as well as it puts pressure
on the a3 pawn.} 12. Bb2 N8a7 13. Re1 O-O 14. Nf1 Rc8 15. Ng3 (15. Ne3 {Shirov}
Bg6 {[%cal Gd8b6,Ga7b5] /\ Qb6=/+}) 15... Bg6 16. Qd2 Qb6 {[%cal Rb6b3]} 17.
Bd1 {[%csl Gb3]} Rc7 {[%cal Gf8c8] black prepares to double his rooks on the
c-file. Slowly, inch by inch black is increasing his pressure on the queenside
and the c-file.} 18. h4 {[%cal Rh4h5]} h6 {[%cal Gg6h7]} 19. Re2 Rfc8 {[%cal
Gc8c1]} 20. Qf4 Nb8 $1 $15 {The knight on c6 was a hindrance in black's path.
So he decides to re-position it.} 21. Re3 Nb5 {[%csl Ra3,Gb5][%cal Gb5a3,Gb5c3]
finally the black knight arrives on its intended square.} (21... Rc6 {/\Qd8-f8,
Nb5 ->Pa3}) 22. Ne2 Nd7 23. Nh2 Rc6 $1 {[%cal Gb6d8,Gd8f8] [#]} 24. Ng4 Qd8 25.
Rh3 Qf8 {[%csl Gf8,Gg7,Gh6] the black queen takes care of white's kingside
attack.} (25... Bxh4 $4 26. Rxh4 Qxh4 27. Nf6+ $18) 26. a4 Na3 (26... Nc7 $15 {
[%cal Gc7a6,Ga6b4]}) 27. Bxa3 $6 (27. h5 $142 Bc2 28. Rc3 Bxd1 29. Rxd1 Bg5 30.
Qf3 Nc2 $15) 27... Bxa3 {[%cal Rc8c1] it's important to note the complete
dominance of the black rooks on the c-file.} 28. Rg3 h5 29. Ne3 Bb2 30. Ra2 Bc1
31. Qg5 Qb4 32. Nf4 Bxe3 33. fxe3 Rc1 $1 34. Nxg6 Rxd1+ $19 35. Kh2 fxg6 36.
Qxg6 Qe7 37. Rf2 $2 Qxh4+ 38. Rh3 Qxf2 {A nice game by Karpov and a model game
on how to play with black in this structure.} 0-1

