1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. c3 cxd4 8. cxd4
Nge7 9. h3 {a strange move by white. There was no need to cover the g4 square.}
Nc8 {A standard manoeuvre in this line, opening up the way for the
dark-squared bishop. We all know this manoeuvre from the Karpov game.} 10. Bg5
Be7 11. Bxe7 N8xe7 12. Nc3 O-O $11 {Black has clearly solved the opening
problems.} 13. Qd2 {[#]} Be4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7f5,Re4f3] The knight will
move to f5 attacking the Pd4. This is a typical way to put pressure on the
d4-pawn.} 14. Ng5 $5 {Andriasian goes for a risky continuation with unclear
consequences.} (14. Rfd1 Nf5 15. Qf4 {was a safer option.}) 14... Nf5 15. Ngxe4
dxe4 16. d5 $1 exd5 (16... Nxe5 $2 17. Qf4 Ng6 18. Qxe4 $14) (16... e3 $5 17.
fxe3 Nxe5 18. Rf4 $1 (18. e4 Qb6+ 19. Kh2 Ne3 $15) 18... Qb6 (18... Qd6 $5) 19.
Re4 f6 20. Bg4 Rad8 21. Bxf5 exf5 22. Rd4 $11) 17. Rad1 Nfd4 (17... d4 18. Nxe4
Re8 (18... Nxe5 $4 19. Qf4 $18 {[%csl Re5,Rf5]}) 19. f4 $1 Ne3 20. Nd6 Re7 21.
Rfe1 Nxd1 22. Rxd1 {[%csl Gd6] with sufficient compensation for the exchange.})
18. Qe3 Qb6 $6 (18... Nxe2+ $1 19. Qxe2 d4 20. Qxe4 (20. Nxe4 Nxe5 21. Qb5 Re8
22. Qxb7 d3 $15 {[%cal Gd8d4]}) 20... Re8 21. f4 Qh4 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gh4e4]
Nice trick. Now White has an unpleasant choice: either to move the knight and
lose the Pe5 or to sacrifice an exchange for a pawn. In both cases Black is
better.}) 19. Nxd5 Qxb2 20. Bc4 Nf5 21. Qxe4 Qxe5 22. Bd3 (22. Qb1 Nfd4 23.
Rfe1 Qg5 24. f4 Qh4 25. Qxb7 Nf3+ 26. gxf3 Qg3+ $11) 22... Qxe4 23. Bxe4 {
White has active pieces which compensate for the lack of a pawn.} g6 (23...
Nfd4 24. Ne7+ Nxe7 25. Rxd4 Rad8 26. Rfd1 Rxd4 27. Rxd4 Nc6 $11) 24. Bxf5 gxf5
25. Ne3 $2 {The is superbly placed on d5, there is no need to move it.} (25.
Rb1 $1 b6 (25... Rad8 26. Rfd1 b6 27. Rbc1 {and White gets back the pawn by
the fork on e7.}) 26. Rfc1 Nd4 27. Rd1 Ne6 28. Ne7+ Kg7 29. Nxf5+ Kf6 30. Nd6
$11) 25... f4 26. Nd5 f3 27. gxf3 {White has got back the pawn but is
practically still a pawn down as his pawns are doubled and Black's two vs one
pawn majority on the queenside is a serious factor in the long run.} Rad8 $17
28. Rfe1 Kg7 29. f4 Rd7 30. Rd3 {[%cal Gd3g3]} Kh6 $1 {A prophylactic move
against the check on g3.} 31. Nb4 Nd4 32. Kf1 Rfd8 33. Red1 Rd6 34. Nc2 Nf5 35.
Rxd6+ Rxd6 36. Rb1 {White must avoid the exchange of rooks in order to retain
some practical chances. The knight endgame is hopeless for White in view of
Black's pawn majority on the queenside.} Rd2 37. Ne3 Nd6 38. Rb4 (38. a4 {
perhaps would have been more stubborn, but, anyway, the endgame is gruesome
for White.}) 38... b5 39. f5 a5 40. Rg4 Rxa2 41. Kg2 b4 42. Rg8 {Trying to
make work the perpetual check mechanism. Black has to play precisely.} Ne4 43.
Ng4+ Kh5 44. Kf3 Ng5+ 45. Kf4 h6 $1 {An important defensive resource.} (45...
Nxh3+ $2 46. Kg3 Ng5 47. Nf6+ Kh6 48. Ng4+ $11) 46. Kg3 Ra3+ 47. Kg2 Kh4 48.
Nxh6 Nxh3 49. Nxf7 Nf4+ 50. Kh2 Rh3+ 51. Kg1 Rc3 {Now Black's king is out of
danger and the two connected passed pawns decide the outcome.} 52. Ne5 b3 53.
Rb8 Kg5 54. Rb5 a4 55. Nf7+ Kg4 56. f6 a3 57. Kh2 Rh3+ 58. Kg1 a2 59. Ra5 b2
60. Ne5+ Kh4 0-1

