{This structure occurs after Black breaks with c6-c5 and White responds with
c2-c3. Then Black advances on the queenside with c5-c4. Generally black will
avoid pushing the pawn to c4 as he would prefer to maintain the pressure on d4
by keeping the pawn on c5. It is only when white provokes or forces black to
play c5-c4 by attacking the c5 pawn with moves like Nb1-d2-b3 or Bc1-e3 that
black goes for c5-c4. Important points to remember in this structure:- 1.
Black's main idea is to create counterplay on the queenside by pushing his
pawns b7-b5 ; a7-a5 and then at an appropriate moment go for the break with
b5-b4.2. White on the other hand will try to create an attack on the kingside
by pushing his pawns and bringing his pieces on the kingside. 3. For Black, it
is beneficial if he has not castled short. With the King in the centre he can
always opt for 0-0-0, thus, side-stepping white's attack on the kingside. 4.
Usually, this structure arises out of the French Defence where black's light
square bishop is on c8, inside blacks pawn chain. With the bishop on c8 black
has to work harder to bring the light square bishop in the game. But the
advantage of this structure arising out of the Caro-Kann defence is that here
the Bishop is already developed on f5, outside the pawn chain. Which makes it
difficult for white to conduct his kingside operations.}  *

