1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Ne7 6. O-O Bg6 7. Nbd2 Nf5 8. c3
c5 9. Nb3 {white attacks the c5 pawn with the knight, thus provoking black to
push c5-c4. White is ready to waste a move for this provocation as he believes
he now gets a free hand on the kingside in the absence on any counterplay in
the centre. But black also gets good play on the queenside.} c4 10. Nbd2 Nc6
11. Ne1 b5 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb5b4] typical pawn advance for black on the queenside.
} 12. g4 {[#]} Nfxd4 $3 {a beautiful piece sacrifice that white underestimated.
Black destroys White's centre completely.} 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Ndf3 Nxe2+ 15.
Qxe2 d4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4] blacks pawns are quite active while white's pieces are
un-coordinated and passive.} 16. a4 d3 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4,Gd3][%cal Gb5d3]} 17. Qe3
b4 {Blacks pawns limits white's pieces perfectly.} 18. Bd2 Rc8 {[%cal Gf8c5]}
19. Rc1 Bc5 20. Qf4 Qd5 {[%csl Gb4,Gc4,Gd3,Gd5,Re1,Rf3] I feel pity for
white's pieces!} 21. Ng2 O-O 22. Qg3 Be4 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5,Ge4]} 23. Nf4 Qd7 24.
Nh5 Ba8 $1 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gd7b7,Gd7a4]} 25. Qf4 f5 $1 {this defends against
white threats on the kingside.} 26. exf6 Qd5 {[%cal Ra8h1] the pressure on the
h1-a8 diagonal is too much to handle.} 27. Rxc4 e5 28. Qg5 Rf7 29. Rxc5 Rxc5
30. fxg7 Rxf3 0-1

