{This is an ideal game to study how black should develop his queenside
counterplay.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O Bg6 7.
Be3 Nh6 8. Nbd2 Nf5 9. c3 Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Nf1 c5 12. Bd3 {white invites
black to play c5-c4 with tempo.} c4 13. Bc2 b5 {[%cal Ga7a5]} 14. Bd2 a5 {
typical pawn advances on the queenside.} 15. Ng3 Nxg3 16. Bxg6 {[#]} fxg6 $1 {
opening the f-file is in blacks favour.} 17. hxg3 b4 {queenside expansion
continues.} 18. Qc2 Nb6 19. a3 {[#]} b3 $5 {[%csl Ra3,Rb2] it seems surprising
that black has completely closed the queenside. But the pawns on b2 and a3
always remains targets till the end as we will find out in the game.} 20. Qc1 {
[%cal Gd2g5]} h6 {[%csl Gg5]} 21. Nh2 g5 {[%csl Rd2] limiting the white's dark
square bishop.} 22. g4 Na4 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ra4b2] the knight always keeps an
eye on the b2 pawn.} 23. Nf1 Kf7 $1 {[%cal Gf7e8,Ge8d7] the black king takes a
safe shelter on the queenside.} 24. Qb1 Ke8 25. Qg6+ Kd7 26. Rab1 Rg8 27. Ng3
Qe8 28. Qxe8+ Rgxe8 29. f3 {[#]} Nxb2 $1 {a crushing blow on the queenside!
The triumph of blacks strategy.} 30. Rxb2 Bxa3 31. Rbb1 a4 {[%csl Ga4,Gb3]
[%cal Ga4a3,Ga3a2]} 32. Nf1 Be7 33. Ra1 a3 34. Reb1 a2 {[%csl Ga2,Gb3,Gc4,Gd5,
Ge6] just look at the beautifull black pawn chain!!!!} 35. Rb2 Ba3 36. Bc1 g6 {
[%csl Ra1,Rb2,Rc1]} 37. Nd2 h5 38. Nf1 hxg4 39. fxg4 Rf8 40. Nh2 Rf4 $1 {
in style!!} 41. Rbxa2 bxa2 42. Rxa2 Bxc1 43. Rxa8 Bb2 44. Ra7+ Kc6 45. Ra6+ Kb5
46. Rxe6 Bxc3 47. Nf3 Bxd4+ 48. Kf1 c3 49. Ke2 c2 50. Rc6 Bc5 51. Nxg5 Rf2+ 0-1

