{This game is an example of why black should not play c5-c4 voluntarily.} 1. e4
c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. c3 {[#]} c4 $6 {
black goes for ...c4 unprovoked.} 8. b3 {white immediately starts hitting on
the queenside before black is able to consolidate.} b5 (8... cxb3 9. axb3 {
[%cal Ga1a7] <->a ()}) 9. a4 a6 (9... cxb3 10. Bxb5 $36) 10. Na3 $1 h6 (10...
Rb8 11. axb5 axb5 12. bxc4 bxc4 13. Qa4 Qd7 14. Nb5 $36 {[%cal Gc1a3] /\Ba3})
11. Bb2 Bxa3 $6 (11... Rb8 12. axb5 axb5 13. bxc4 bxc4 14. Qa4 Qb6 15. Nd2 Nge7
16. Naxc4 dxc4 17. Nxc4 Qb3 18. Nd6+ Kd7 $13) 12. Bxa3 Nge7 13. Bc5 $1 {
[%csl Gc5]} O-O 14. b4 $1 {White closes the queenside with his dark square
bishop beautifully placed on c5!} Rb8 15. Nh4 Bh7 16. f4 (16. a5 {/\f4 ->>>})
16... Re8 (16... a5 $132 17. axb5 Rxb5 18. Qa4 Qb8 19. Bxe7 Nxe7 20. bxa5 Nc6)
17. a5 $16 {the queenside is now completely closed and white has a free hand
on the kingside.} *

