{This structure arises after Black breaks with c7-c5 and white responds in a
similar way by breaking with c2-c4. Important points to remember in this
structure:- 1. On Black's c7-c5, White usually responds with c2-c4 when he
thinks he is ready to open up the centre. 2. Usually White will break with
c2-c4 when he is ahead in development and hopes to exploit his lead in
development by creating immediate pressure with his pieces in the centre. 3.
Usually, there will be pawn exchanges in the centre which lead to the open 'c'
and 'd' files. In this situation, one of the main plans for white is to gain
control of the d6 square with the help of his e5 pawn. A very important
strategy for white is to exchange the dark square bishops so that he can
dominate the d6 square. 4. After the pawn exchanges in the centre, Black on
the other hand makes sure that he gets a firm control of the d5 square and
will try to cement his knight on d5. He will try to exchange as many pieces as
possible and try to exploit white's over-extended centre (pawn on e5) in the
endgame. 5. In general Black should avoid the exchange of his Dark Square
Bishop.}  *

