1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Ne7 6. O-O c5 7. c4 Nbc6 8. Na3 a6
9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bg5 {Should black exchange the dark square bishops with ...
Be7? [#]} Qd7 $1 {[%cal Gh7h6]} (10... Be7 $2 {exchanging the dark squares
would be a big strategical mistake!} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nc4 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal
Rc4d6] now the white knight gets a firm square on d6 where it will be very
active.} O-O 13. Nd6 {[%cal Rd4c5] white threatens dc5.} cxd4 14. Nxd4 $16 {
[%csl Gd6][%cal Rd4f5] threatening N4xf5, which prevents black from taking the
e5 pawn. Due to the knight on d6 white is clearly better.}) 11. dxc5 h6 {
first, it is important to push the dark square bishop from g5.} 12. Bh4 {[#]}
Nf4 $1 {this forces the exchange of Queens. As we know, endgames are generally
good for black.} (12... Bxc5 $5 13. Nc4 Nf4 $17) 13. Qxd7+ Kxd7 14. Rfd1+ Kc7
15. Bf1 Bg4 (15... Bxc5 $142 16. Rac1 Bxa3 17. bxa3 g5 18. Bg3 Rhd8 $15) 16.
Bg3 Bxf3 17. gxf3 g5 18. Rac1 Bg7 19. Nc4 Rad8 20. Re1 Rd5 21. a3 Nxe5 22. Nxe5
Rxe5 23. Red1 Rd5 24. Rxd5 exd5 25. Rc2 Re8 26. Bxf4+ gxf4 27. Be2 Re5 28. b4
Rg5+ 29. Kf1 Rh5 30. Kg2 Rg5+ 31. Kf1 Rh5 32. Kg2 Rg5+ 1/2-1/2

