{This structure usually arises after White breaks with c2-c4 before black gets
a chance to break with c6-c5. Important points to remember:- 1. White breaks
with c2-c4 immediately in order to discourage black from breaking with ...c5.2.
In most cases, black will sooner or later exchange pawns with ...dc4. Once
this happens, Black will enjoy complete control on the d5 square where he
would prefer to place his Knight. 3. After the pawn exchange on c4 White will
try to use his space advantage to create pressure on the kingside by gaining
more space with h2-h4-h5. He will also keep the c5 square under control making
it very difficult for black to achieve the ...c5 break comfortably. 4. Most of
the time white goes for this structure only after inserting h2-h4 and h7-h5
beforehand.}  *

