1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. c4 e6 5. Nc3 Ne7 6. Nge2 Nd7 7. Ng3 Bg6 8. a3
dxc4 {a typical exchange in this structure. Black gets a firm control on the
d5 square.} 9. Bxc4 Nb6 10. Bb3 {[#]} Qd7 {[%cal Ga8d8]} 11. O-O Rd8 {[%csl
Rd4] another problem for white is the pawn on d4 on which black puts pressure
on the d-file.} 12. Be3 Ned5 {[%csl Gb6,Gd5] the usual placement of the black
knights on b6 and d5, maintaining firm control of the d5 square.} 13. h4 h5 14.
Bg5 {[#]} Be7 {exchanging the dark square bishops is not a problem here for
black as white's pawn on h4 and d4 will also be weak after the exchanges.} 15.
Nce4 Bxg5 16. Nxg5 {[#]} Nc7 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rc7b5] a nice manoeuvre!} 17.
Ne2 Nb5 18. Nf4 Bf5 19. Nxh5 Kf8 {[%csl Rd4] now the d4 pawn is doomed.} 20.
Ng3 Nxd4 21. Nxf5 Nxf5 22. g3 Qxd1 $1 {exchanging queens is always recommended!
} 23. Rfxd1 Ke7 24. Nf3 Nd7 25. Bc2 Nh6 26. Re1 Nb6 27. b4 (27. Bb3 Rd3 $17)
27... Nc4 {[%csl Gc4]} 28. Re2 Rd7 29. Kf1 Rhd8 30. Rae1 Ng4 {[%csl Re5]} 31.
a4 Rd5 {[%csl Re5]} 32. Bb3 Rd3 33. Bxc4 Rxf3 34. Rc1 Rd4 {blacks rooks are
very active compared to white's. It is instructive to see how Black exploit
the weak pawns in white's camp.} 35. a5 a6 {[%csl Ra5,Rb4] fixing weaknesses
on the queenside.} 36. Kg1 Ra3 $1 {[%cal Ra3a4]} 37. Kg2 Ra4 38. f3 Nh6 39. Rb2
Nf5 {[%cal Gf5e3]} 40. Kf2 Ra3 41. Be2 Ne3 42. h5 Kf8 43. b5 axb5 44. a6 bxa6
45. Rxc6 Rd8 46. g4 Nd5 47. Bf1 Ke7 48. Rbc2 Rb8 49. Rc8 Rxc8 50. Rxc8 f6 51.
exf6+ Kxf6 52. Rf8+ Ke7 53. Ra8 b4 54. g5 Ra2+ 55. Kg3 Ra1 56. Ra7+ Kf8 57. Kf2
Ra2+ 58. Kg1 Nf4 59. h6 gxh6 60. gxh6 Kg8 61. Bc4 Rc2 62. Rc7 Kh8 63. Rc8+ Kh7
64. Bd3+ Nxd3 65. Rxc2 b3 66. Rc7+ Kxh6 67. Kf1 b2 68. Rb7 a5 69. Rb3 a4 70.
Rb6 a3 0-1

