{This structure arises when White advances on the kingside with h2-h4 and
black responds with h7-h5. Here we will only consider cases where white does
not go for the c2-c4 break immediately. Whenever white breaks with c2-c4,
black will usually exchange on c4 when we transpose to structure no. 5.
Important points to remember in this structure:- 1. After inserting h4 and ...
h5, white gets a good control of the g5 square which he tries to exploit by
putting his Bishop and creating some uncomfort for Black. 2. Black will, of
course, go for his typical break with ...c5 and create a play on the queenside.
3. After the exchange of the light-squared bishops, Black should try to
establish his knight on the f5 square which helps is putting pressure on the
d4 pawn. 4. If the Black knight on f5 is challenged with Ng3, when is most
cases Black supports his Knight with g7-g6 and prepares to recapture of f5
with ...gf5.}  *

