1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 {white goes for it immediately.} Bd7
(5... Be4 6. f3 Bh7 7. e6 $1 {can be slightly uncomfortable for black.}) 6. Nd2
e6 7. Nb3 {with this manoeuvre white plays against Black ...c5 break.} c5 $1 {
going straight for it nonetheless.} 8. Nxc5 Bxc5 9. dxc5 Qa5+ 10. c3 Qxc5 {
black has lost the pair of bishops and also his important dark square bishops,
but in return, he has managed to open up the queenside. We can see that
white's pieces are still undeveloped which black hopes to exploit!} 11. h5 {
[%csl Gg4,Gh5] white has got his ideal pawn formation in the kingside and
gained space, but it has cost a lot of valuable time for him!} Ne7 12. Nf3 Nbc6
13. Bf4 {[#] Can you find a good strategical move for black?} g5 $1 {a very
important move for black. Now white will never be able to support his e5 pawn
with f2-f4 and this pawn now always needs constant care.} 14. Bg3 O-O-O $1 {
the black king runs away on the queenside where it feels much safer} 15. Bd3 d4
$1 16. c4 {[#]} Nf5 $5 17. gxf5 exf5 18. Bh2 f4 {[%csl Gf4,Gg5,Rh2,Rh5,Gh6]}
19. Qb3 Bg4 20. Be4 Rhe8 21. O-O Bxh5 22. Ne1 Qxe5 {black has regained
material but white's position is very passive.} 23. Bxc6 bxc6 24. Qh3+ g4 25.
Qg2 Qe4 26. Nd3 g3 $1 27. fxg3 f3 28. Qd2 Qe3+ 29. Rf2 Bg4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3,Rf2,
Gf3,Rh2] poor white pieces.} 30. Re1 Re6 $3 31. Rd1 Rde8 32. Nf4 Re4 33. Kh1
Qxd2 34. Rfxd2 f2 35. Rf1 {[#]} Rxf4 $1 36. Kg2 (36. gxf4 Bf3#) 36... Rfe4 37.
Rfxf2 f5 38. Bg1 c5 39. a3 a5 40. b4 axb4 41. axb4 cxb4 42. Rb2 f4 43. gxf4 Rg8
44. Kh2 Re3 45. Rf1 Rh3+ 46. Kg2 Bf5+ 47. Kf2 b3 0-1

