{This structure arises after white goes for the kingside advance g2-g4 before
playing h2-h4. Important points to remember:- 1. Most of the time white plays
g2-g4 to attack the bishop on f5 or the Knight on f5.2. This advance usually
happens before h2-h4.3. The most important idea for black in this structure is
to look for an h7-h5 break on the kingside. If Black manages to achieve that
comfortably then either he will gain permanent access to the f5 square (in
case white captures gh5) or he will gain control of the open h-file (in case
white supports his g4 pawn with h2-h3).}  *

