1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Ne7 6. O-O Bg6 {The main idea of
this bishop retreat is to post the knight on f5. The B goes to e7 and the
other N to d7. In this way, Black is a little cramped but all his pieces find
ideal squares.} 7. Nbd2 (7. Nh4 {is a logical move to eliminate the B on g6
but Black can play strongly with} c5 $1 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. c3 cxd4 10. cxd4 Nbc6
$11 {[%cal Ge7f5] with a comfortable opening position.}) 7... Nf5 8. c4 {
Not very often played, nonetheless a very natural move.} (8. Nb3 {is the
normal way to play this position.} Nd7 9. Bd2 {White is waiting for Black to
play Be7 so that he can play g4 when after Nh4 Nxh4 the knight cannot be
recaptured with the Q.} Be7 10. g4 {is the main line.}) 8... Be7 9. g4 {
As mentioned previously, once the bishop is developed on e7, g4 becomes much
more enticing for White as Nh4 Nxh4 cannot be met with Qxh4.} Nh6 $5 {The
start of a very interesting idea that was seen in a similar position in the
game Alexei Shirov-Dragan Solak. The idea is very deep and will be revealed on
the next move itself.} (9... Nh4 {is the obvious move and not so bad.} 10. Nxh4
Bxh4 11. f4 {This is the usual idea. To exchange the knights and threaten
f4-f5.} f5 12. exf6 Bxf6 (12... Qxf6 $2 13. Nf3 $18) 13. Nf3 O-O 14. g5 Be7 15.
Qb3 $14 {with a more pleasant position for White but with a lot of fight in it.
}) 10. h3 {[#]} Ng8 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7f5,Gf5h6,Gh6g8] The knight makes a
complete tour from g8-e7-f5-h6 back to g8! Black wants to open the kingside
with h7-h5. As we know already, with white's pawn on g4 we should always try
to play h7-h5. After h7-h5, either we will get control on the f5 square or get
control of the open h-file.} 11. Ne1 h5 12. Ng2 (12. gxh5 Bf5 {looks
comfortable for Black.}) (12. f4 hxg4 13. hxg4 {The threat is f5 but it can be
stopped with} Nh6 14. Ng2 c5 $5 15. cxd5 Qxd5 $15 {Black is alright.}) 12...
hxg4 13. hxg4 dxc4 (13... Nd7 {not releasing the tension.} 14. Nf4 Bh7 15. Nh5
Kf8 $13) 14. Nxc4 Be4 $6 (14... Na6 15. Nf4 Bh7 16. Nh5 {looks risky but Black
seems to be holding on after} Kf8 $13 {[%cal Ga6b4,Gb4d5]}) 15. f3 (15. Bg5 $1
{would have been a nice tactical idea taking advantage of the fact that Nd6+
would drop the e4-bishop. Black now has to resort to the ugly} f6 {but after}
16. Bf4 $14 {the weakening of his structure with f6 is not what White would
have wanted to do.}) 15... Bd5 16. Nce3 c5 {A logical move trying to develop
the knight to c6.} 17. Nf4 Bc6 {Ankit believes in the solidity of his position
and delays development. It might have been better to develop a piece with} (
17... Nc6 18. Nexd5 exd5 19. Bb5 $5 Rc8 (19... Bg5 20. dxc5 $16) (19... Nh6 20.
Kg2 $16) 20. Kg2 a6 21. Bxc6+ Rxc6 $13 {We have an extremely unconventional
position but one in which Black is not worse.}) 18. d5 {White should
definitely be better here. He is ahead in development by leaps and bounds. The
only factor against him is the open h-file but it shouldn't be such a huge
factor.} exd5 19. Nfxd5 $6 (19. Nexd5 {was much more logical for the pure
reason that the knight on f4 will be much more valuable than the knight on e3.}
Bxd5 (19... Nd7 20. e6 $1 $18) (19... Bh4 20. e6 $1 fxe6 21. Nxe6 $18) 20. Qxd5
(20. Nxd5 Nc6) 20... Nc6 (20... Qxd5 21. Nxd5 $16) 21. Bb5 $1 Qxd5 22. Nxd5
O-O-O 23. Bxc6 bxc6 24. Ne3 $14 {White is much better in this endgame.}) 19...
Bh4 $5 {Objectively this is not such a great move but the interesting remark
is because of the interesting sacrificial idea that Black came up with.} (19...
Nd7 20. Nf5 Nxe5 $1 21. Bf4 Qxd5 22. Qxd5 Bxd5 23. Bxe5 Bf6 24. Bb5+ Kf8 25.
Bd6+ Ne7 26. Rfe1 Be6 $11 {all this looks really scary for Black but thanks to
the precise defence he is fine here and has no problems.}) 20. Kg2 (20. Nf4 $5
{would have exchanged the queens and retained a clear edge for White.} Bg3 (
20... Qg5 $2 21. Nf5 $18) 21. Qxd8+ Kxd8 22. Nf5 $18) 20... Bg3 $5 {A very
brave sacrifice. White has a way to keep an advantage here but for that, he
has to decline the gift that he has been offered. Not so easy to do that!} 21.
Kxg3 $2 {Naiditsch's sense of danger eluded him in this game. Black's pieces
though currently undeveloped suddenly start to co-ordinate perfectly to launch
an attack on the white king.} (21. Nf6+ $1 {was the best defence and maybe the
most practical choice in this position.} gxf6 (21... Nxf6 22. Qxd8+ Kxd8 23.
Kxg3 $16) 22. Qxd8+ Kxd8 23. Kxg3 fxe5 24. Bd2 $16 {It is difficult to assess
this resulting position. White is a pawn down. True but all the other factors
are on his side. He has the bishop pair. His knight is looking at some juicy
squares like c4 and f5 and the white rooks are quickly co-ordinating
themselves to hassle the uncastled black king. White is clearly better here.})
21... Qh4+ 22. Kf4 (22. Kg2 Qh2#) 22... Qh2+ 23. Ke4 Nd7 $1 {Attacking the
e5-pawn. Black is a piece down but with the king on e4 the attack is bound to
succeed.} 24. Kd3 (24. f4 O-O-O 25. Bc4 Ngf6+ 26. exf6 Nxf6+ 27. Kd3 (27. Kf3
Rh3#) 27... Nxd5 $19) 24... O-O-O {White is going to lose material soon. Black
is patient and brings all his pieces into play.} 25. Kc2 {Naiditsch chooses
the most practical way to play trying to return the material but get his king
to safety.} (25. f4 Bxd5 26. Nxd5 Ndf6 $1 $19) 25... Nxe5 {Such positions are
very difficult for the defending side. There are no clear threats but his
position is dangerous. In such a situation it is easy to go wrong and
Naiditsch isn't able to find the only path to safety.} 26. Qd2 $2 {A mistake
but such mistakes don't happen in a vacuum. It was because of the sustained
pressure.} (26. Bd2 $1 {was the best. The idea is to connect the queens with
both the rooks so that Rh1 is possible.} Bxd5 27. Nxd5 Qh7+ (27... Rxd5 28. Rh1
Qxh1 29. Qxh1 Rxh1 30. Rxh1 $11) 28. Kc3 (28. Kc1 Rxd5 $17) 28... Rxd5 29. Rh1
Rd3+ (29... Qxh1 30. Qxh1 Rxh1 31. Rxh1 Nf6 $11) 30. Kc2 Nh6 31. Bxd3 Qxd3+ 32.
Kc1 Nxf3 33. g5 Nxd2 34. Qxd2 Qf3 35. Rd1 Nf5 $11 {A crazy and complicated
line which ends with an assessment of 0.00. Though to tell you the truth it is
much easier to play as Black here than White.}) (26. Kb1 Bxd5 27. Nxd5 Qh7+ $1
{It is easy to miss this check.} 28. Qc2 Rxd5 $17) 26... Nf6 $1 27. Ne7+ Kb8 (
27... Kc7 {was also fine but why would anyone allow the opponent to check on
a5.} 28. Qa5+ Kb8 29. Nxc6+ Nxc6 $19) 28. Nxc6+ Nxc6 29. Bd3 (29. Qe1 Nd4+ 30.
Kb1 Qh7+ (30... Nxe2 {also wins.}) 31. Nf5 Nxf5 $19) 29... Nb4+ 30. Kb1 Qc7 {
Keeping the queens on the board also makes sense because the white king is
still quite exposed.} (30... Qxd2 31. Bxd2 Rxd3 32. Bxb4 cxb4 33. Nc4 (33. Nf5
Rh2 $19) 33... Rh2 $19 {[%csl Ra1] The rook on a1 is totally out of play and I
think this was the easiest way for Black to win.}) 31. g5 Rxd3 32. Qe1 Nfd5 (
32... Qh2 $1 {was a completely crushing move. The idea? Well, it is to play
the queen to h7 from where it will deliver the final blow!} 33. Rf2 (33. gxf6
Rxe3 (33... Qh7 34. Rh1 $1 $14) 34. Qd2 Qh7+ $19) 33... Qh7 $1 $19 {[%cal
Gc7h2,Gh2h7] a difficult idea to see but totally crushing.}) 33. Ng4 Nb6 (33...
c4 {with the idea of c3-c2 is a strong one.}) 34. Qe5 {White tries to exchange
the queens and tries to salvage this otherwise lost position.} Qxe5 $6 (34...
Nc4 35. Qxc7+ (35. Qxg7 Qd8 $1 $19 {[%cal Gc4d2,Gc4a3]}) 35... Kxc7 $19) 35.
Nxe5 Rd4 36. Nxf7 (36. Be3 {would have put up much better resistance. It is
possible that both the players were under acute time pressure and couldn't
make the most accurate moves in the position.} Rd5 37. Nxf7 Rf8 38. g6 Nc4 39.
Bf4+ Ka8 40. Rg1 $17 {Black is better but White is still fighting.}) 36... Rh2
37. Be3 $2 {The final mistake.} (37. a3 Nd3 38. Ra2 {was necessary although
White is just losing after} Nxc1 39. Rxc1 Nc4 $19 {[%cal Gc4d2,Gd2b3]}) 37...
Nd3 $1 (37... Nc4 {was equally strong.} 38. Bxd4 cxd4 39. Ne5 Nd2+ 40. Kc1 Nxf1
$19) 38. Bc1 (38. Bxd4 cxd4 $19) 38... Nc4 39. Rd1 Nxc1 $19 {Not a perfect
game but very entertaining.} (39... Nxc1 40. Kxc1 Rxd1+ 41. Kxd1 Rh1+ $19 {
loses a rook. A very interesting and intense struggle and shows that even the
best in the world make mistakes when put under pressure.}) 0-1

