{[%evp 0,34,16,28,65,58,68,68,61,23,88,32,74,82,78,76,60,67,87,-22,-22,-59,-80,
-98,-69,-94,-94,-81,-66,-163,-163,-198,-205,-93,-127,-219,-169] Attacking
Concepts in Caro Can Advanced Variation - The idea Bf5-d7} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3.
e5 Bf5 4. g4 {Very sharp continuation which suits Shirov's style.} Bd7 {
I like this idea. Black provokes g2-g4 and is ready to start his counterplay
with c6-c5. The point is that the pawn on g4 is hanging in many lines. White
can't play Nf3} (4... Be4 $5 {is the most popular choice} 5. f3 Bg6 6. h4 $6 (
6. e6 $1 {is the recent trend in this line and it seems that White has the
upper hand here}) 6... h5 7. e6 Qd6 $1 {Black is doing fine here}) 5. c4 e6 6.
Nc3 c5 $1 {Anand realizes the potential here for Black} (6... Ne7 {is
Mamedyarov's choice here}) 7. cxd5 exd5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bg2 $146 (9. Qxd5 $6
Qb6 $17 {Black has tremendous compensation for the sacrificing pawn.}) (9. Nxd5
$2 Bc6 10. Bg2 Ne7 $17 11. Ne3 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 Ng6) 9... Ne7 10. h3 Qb6 11. Qe2
O-O {Black is already better.} 12. Nf3 d4 $1 13. Ne4 Bb5 {Now it is over.
White's king will stay in the centre} 14. Qd2 Nbc6 15. a3 Ng6 16. b4 Be7 17.
Bb2 Rfd8 {This was one of the worst Shirov's games} 0-1

