{[%evp 0,35,21,21,75,68,69,57,82,49,45,-8,-9,-102,12,9,1,-333,-321,-277,-39,
-119,-39,30,38,60,189,189,208,196,224,221,224,274,287,329,311,317]} 1. e4 c6 2.
d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 {The latest trend in the Advanced variation. White grabs
some space on the queenside and is threatening g2-g4 to win a piece.} h5 {
Black has several other ways to continue, but this is the most popular one.} (
4... Qc7 $5 {is an interesting try} 5. g4 Bd7 {with similar ideas as in
Anand's game}) 5. Bg5 $5 {Is a very interesting try. White is stopping e7-e6.}
(5. Bd3 {Is by far the main move in this position. Without the inclusion of
h2-h4 and h7-h5 this would be harmless, but now Black's kingside is weakened
and White can use the "g5" square for his pieces.}) 5... Qb6 {the only logical
move.} 6. Bd3 Bxd3 (6... Qxd4 {This move was suggested in many books as a
refutation of 5.Bg5, but the things are not that simple here.} 7. Nf3 (7. Bxf5
$2 Qxe5+ $19) 7... Qg4 8. Bxf5 Qxf5 9. c4 {White has some compensation for the
sacrificed pawn.} (9. O-O $5)) 7. Qxd3 {Critical position for the evaluation
of this line.} Qxb2 $2 {this move is losing on a spot} (7... e6 $5 {is
possible, but then we transpose to a favorable variation for White after:} 8.
Nd2 Nd7 9. Ngf3 Ne7 10. c4 Nf5 11. O-O $14) (7... Qa6 $1 {The best move for
Black. With the knight still on b1, c2-c4 is not possible.} 8. Qxa6 (8. Qf3 $5)
8... Nxa6 {this endgame is around equal}) 8. e6 $3 $18 Qxa1 9. Qb3 $1 {The
point of White's previous move. Now the queen is trapped, and Qxb7 is a major
threat} Qxd4 (9... b5 10. Nf3 {[%cal Rg5d2,Rd2c3]}) 10. Qxb7 fxe6 11. Be3 Qa4
12. Qxa8 Qa5+ 13. Nd2 Qd8 14. Ngf3 $18 {The rest is agony and White won in a
few moves.} Nf6 15. O-O g6 16. Rb1 Nbd7 17. Qxc6 Bg7 18. Ng5 1-0

