{[%evp 0,48,23,20,47,53,53,53,53,48,38,44,50,50,56,16,17,3,30,10,7,5,13,14,13,
-29,-30,-38,-15,-91,-20,-48,-15,-37,-2,-58,-36,-63,-24,-63,-63,-349,-311,-380,
-792,-792,-920,-29989,-29990,-29999,-30000] In this game Black comes up with
an interesting attacking concept on the kigside.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5
4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 {The Short Variation - This is the main line in Advanced
variation nowadays. The main problem for Black is that it is not easy to
develop the kingside. Both minor pieces have only one good square "e7". I am
not going deep into theory here.} Ne7 6. O-O Ng6 {very interesting development
scheme for Black. The drawback of this setup is that the "f5" bishop is not
feeling very comfortable.} 7. a4 Nd7 8. Be3 f6 $1 {In the Advanced Variation
Black has two possible pawn breaks. One is "c6-c5" and the other is "f7-f6".
In this case, the second one is better, because Black's knight puts pressure
on "e5" and White will be forced to exchange "e5xf6".} 9. exf6 Qxf6 {The
structure resembles "Tarrasch Variation" (3.Nd2) in French Defence, but with
the big difference that the light-squared bishop is active on "f5"} 10. c4 Bd6
11. Qb3 $2 {This is conceptually wrong because all Black's pieces are
concentrating on the kingside and White will need the queen for the defence}
Rb8 12. Nc3 O-O 13. a5 a6 14. Na4 {White continues to play on the wrong side
of the board. There is nothing that he can do on the queenside.} h6 {with the
idea to stop Ng5 or Bg5} 15. Rfe1 Kh8 {Black is not in a hurry to start any
concrete actions and just slowly improves his position.} 16. Rad1 Rf7 17. Nb6
Nxb6 18. axb6 Rbf8 {Six Black's pieces are on the kingside and are ready to
attack the king. White has not enough defensive resources there. It is obvious
that Black's attack is unstoppable.} 19. Qc3 Be4 {[%cal Rf8f3]} 20. b4 {
Matinian stays loyal to his strategy to play on the wrong side.} Nh4 21. Nxh4
Bxh2+ 22. Kxh2 Qxh4+ 23. Kg1 Bxg2 24. Bf1 Qh1# 0-1

[Event "World Rapid 2017"]
[Site "Riyadh KSA"]
[Date "2017.12.27"]
[Round "8.9"]
[White "Karjakin, Sergey"]
[Black "Esipenko, Andrey"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "B11"]
[WhiteElo "2760"]
[BlackElo "2564"]
[Annotator "GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[PlyCount "58"]
[EventDate "2017.12.26"]
[EventType "swiss (rapid)"]
[EventRounds "15"]
[EventCountry "SAU"]
[SourceTitle "Petar"]
[SourceDate "2020.01.10"]
[SourceVersion "9"]
[SourceVersionDate "2020.01.10"]
[SourceQuality "1"]

{Two Knights Variation In the following game, we can see one of the main
attacking concepts in the "Two Knights Variation. White is attacking the
queenside and Black is organizing an exemplary attack. After this game, White
starts to choose more frequently the setups with a short castle.} 1. e4 c6 2.
Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Bg4 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 Nf6 6. d3 e6 7. Bd2 {This is one of the
old tabyas in the "Two Knights Variation". White is planning to castle a long
and to start rolling his pawns on the kingside.} Qb6 8. O-O-O d4 $1 {Strong
idea. Black releases the tension in the center, but wins space and kicks the
defender of White's king.} 9. Ne2 c5 {Black is preparing Nb8-c6 and does not
hurry to castle kingside. On many occasions, the king will be safer on the
queenside or in the centre.} 10. e5 (10. g4 $5 {was probably stronger, but
Black is doing very good here as well.}) 10... Nd5 11. Nf4 Nb4 $1 {Black
doesn't want to exchange his attacking pieces. The knight on f4 is not doing
much} 12. Kb1 (12. Bxb4 cxb4 $17 {is clearly in Black's favour}) 12... Nd7 {
keeping "c6" square available for the other knight} 13. Qe4 Nc6 14. Nh5 O-O-O {
White was ready to attack on the kingside, but the king escaped on the other
flang. Now, it is time for Black to start building his attack.} 15. f4 $2 (15.
c4 {was mandatory}) 15... c4 $1 {Now Black includes two more pieces into the
attack ("Nd7" and "Bf8") The important rule is that an attack is successful
when at least three pieces are taking part in it. In this case we have at
least four attackers and no defenders. The rest of the game is a beautiful
conversion, but this was the decisive point of the game.} 16. dxc4 Ba3 17. Bc1
Nc5 18. Qf3 d3 $1 {cutting the queen off} 19. cxd3 (19. Bxd3 Bxb2 20. Bxb2 Na4
$19) 19... Na4 20. Rd2 Nd4 21. Qf2 Nc3+ 22. Ka1 Qb3 $3 {The move which shocked
the chess world with its beauty} 23. bxc3 Qxc3+ 24. Bb2 Bxb2+ 25. Rxb2 Qc1+ 26.
Rb1 Nc2+ 27. Qxc2 Qxc2 28. g3 b5 29. cxb5 Rd4 {Amazing win by the young
Esipenko against the World Champion contender} 0-1

