{[%evp 0,68,19,31,84,55,69,59,60,29,29,16,57,35,46,27,15,13,13,-1,-1,-6,-2,-2,
-8,-5,-3,-4,1,0,-9,-18,-7,-8,-3,22,12,18,-3,11,17,-25,-5,4,-23,-2,0,-57,-3,-56,
-75,-33,-33,-48,-45,-185,-170,-199,-199,-230,-228,-330,-391,-421,-427,-531,
-596,-596,-618,-862,-901] Exchange Variation Firouzja comes up with a
completely new concept - 12...Nh5, 16...Kh8, 17...Rg8 A great example for an
attack with same side castling} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. c3
Bg4 6. Qb3 Qc7 7. h3 Bd7 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. O-O e6 10. Re1 Bd6 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Nbd2
{After the opening moves, we reach a typical position for the Exchange
Variation in Caro Can.} Nh5 $3 {Firouzja shows an amazing concept. His plan is
Nh5 followed by f6-g5, Nf4, Kh8, Rg8} 13. Qd1 f6 14. Be3 Nf4 15. Bf1 {White
wanted to keep his bishop pair} g5 $1 16. c4 Kh8 $3 {It resembles Fisher Kh8
the idea in Hedgehog structure.} 17. Rc1 Rg8 18. Bxf4 Bxf4 19. b4 {The engine
still gives equality, but in my opinion, the game is already over.} Qd6 20. b5
Ne7 21. c5 {releasing the tension on the queenside gives Black free hand to
organize his attack} (21. Rc3 $5 {was the best defence}) 21... Qc7 22. g3 g4
23. hxg4 Rxg4 24. Bh3 Rg7 25. Kh1 e5 (25... Bxg3 $1 {was stronger}) 26. Bxd7
Qxd7 27. Nh2 Qh3 28. Rg1 Rag8 $19 {The triumph of Black's strategy} 29. Qe2 e4
30. Rc3 Nf5 31. Nxe4 dxe4 32. Qxe4 Bxg3 33. Rg2 Re7 34. Qb1 Rge8 0-1

