{[%evp 0,56,21,28,65,57,67,47,56,33,40,16,31,-42,37,26,41,-12,0,10,36,18,8,-7,
-26,-24,-24,-24,-23,-23,-4,-14,-36,-82,-60,-138,-138,-287,-290,-194,-205,-161,
-170,-146,-263,-327,-416,-408,-347,-511,-504,-991,-942,-29989,-29990,-29991,
-29992,-29993,-29994] Exchange Variation} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. h3 g6 7. Bf4 Bf5 8. Be2 {The new trend in this line. White is
avoiding the exchange of the bishop and wants to prove that the bishop is not
well placed on "f5"} e6 9. Nd2 h5 {g2-g4 was the threat} 10. Qb3 Bd6 11. Qxb7
$6 {questionable decision} ({Svidler tried to improve Shuvalova's play, but
didn't achieve anything after:} 11. Bg5 Rb8 12. Ngf3 Kf8 13. O-O Kg7 14. c4 Be7
15. Bf4 Bd6 (15... dxc4 $5 {and Black can continue the game} 16. Nxc4 Rc8) 16.
Bg5 Be7 17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Bg5 Be7 {1/2-1/2 (18) Svidler,P (2729)-Riazantsev,A 
(2645) Douglas 2019}) 11... Bxf4 12. Qxc6+ Kf8 {The king is just going to hide
on "g7"} 13. Ngf3 Kg7 14. Nb3 Rb8 15. O-O {Black has two attacking ideas in
this position. One is to start pushing "h" and "g" pawns and the other which
was played in the game is to play Ne4-g5} Ne4 $1 16. Rad1 Ng5 {[%cal Rf5e4,
Rg5f3,Rd8g5]} 17. g3 $2 {Shuvalova probably panicked here and lost quickly
after} Nxh3+ 18. Kg2 h4 {The position is already winning and Gyrya easily
defeated her opponent} 19. Rh1 hxg3 20. fxg3 Rc8 21. Qa6 Qc7 22. Nh4 Be4+ 23.
Bf3 Bxg3 24. Rxh3 Rxh4 25. Bxe4 Rxh3 26. Kxh3 Rh8+ 27. Kg2 Rh2+ 28. Kg1 Qf4 {
To conclude, "The Exchange Variation" is not "risk-free" for White.} 0-1

