{[%evp 0,43,26,28,65,57,61,26,44,26,48,63,53,6,48,53,41,34,34,-166,-135,-116,
-119,-119,119,-130,-98,-103,163,231,238,309,309,329,356,416,416,190,261,316,
316,300,246,285,748,644] Classical Sacrifice} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4.
Nxe4 Nd7 {is not that popular and 4...Nf6 and 4...Bf5 are more frequently
played. However the line is still completely playable and we shouldn't forget
that it was Karpov's favorite.} 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. Ng5 h6 (6... e6 {is of course
the main move}) 7. Ne6 $1 {A simple but beautful tactic that you should
definitely remember!} Qa5+ 8. Bd2 Qb6 9. Nf3 $3 {The concept which impressed
me a lot in my childhood when I studied this game. White can just leave the
knight on e6 and not worry about fxe6.} fxe6 10. Bg6+ Kd8 11. O-O {[%cal Rf1e1,
Rc2c4] Black is a piece up, but his position is completely lost.} c5 $6 {
Opening the position is favoring White} 12. c4 cxd4 13. Nxd4 e5 14. c5 $1 $18
Nxc5 15. Ba5 $1 exd4 16. Qxd4+ Ncd7 17. Bxb6+ axb6 18. Rac1 e5 19. Qc4 Bc5 20.
Rfd1 Rf8 21. b4 Bd4 22. Rxd4 1-0

