{[%evp 0,67,22,22,71,75,75,24,32,38,61,67,46,10,104,65,42,31,34,10,10,10,20,7,
7,14,39,8,10,-3,32,-47,-47,-47,-31,0,0,107,88,-100,-84,-84,58,-43,-49,-5,48,48,
66,0,0,128,161,125,103,103,114,114,193,212,281,258,331,331,331,314,344,344,420,
420] Classical Variation 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4 Bf5} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4
4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Ngf6
11. Bd2 e6 12. O-O-O Be7 (12... Qc7) 13. Qe2 O-O 14. Kb1 c5 15. d5 $3 {An
amazing novelty at that time. The concept is very deep. White is slowing down
Black's counterplay on the queenside by keeping the c-file closed. Also,
White's "g3" knight will come to "f5" or "e4" without being exchanged and
Black's king will be in danger. As we know in positions with opposite castling
the primary idea is to start the attack first} exd5 $6 {now the "f5" square is
available for White's knight} (15... Nxd5 16. Ne4 {[%cal Rg2g4] is also very
good for White. There is no easy defense against the g4-g5 idea.}) 16. Bxh6 $1
gxh6 17. Nf5 $1 Re8 18. Nxh6+ Kf8 (18... Kg7 $2 {is losing on a spot} 19. Qd2
Rh8 20. Nf5+ $18) 19. Ng5 (19. Qd2 $3 {was very strong} Qb6 (19... Ng8 20. Nxf7
$1 {is the final blow. Now Black's position is falling apart} Kxf7 21. h6 d4
22. Qf4+ Bf6 23. h7 Ne7 24. Ng5+ Kg7 25. h8=Q+ {[%cal Rg5e6]}) 20. Qg5 Bd6 21.
Nf5 $18) 19... Qb6 20. Qf3 Ne5 21. Qg3 {the threat is Nh7 followed by Qg8x} Bd6
22. Nf5 $1 {again Nh7+ is the threat} Qxb2+ $1 {the only defence} 23. Kxb2 Nc4+
24. Kb3 $5 (24. Kc1 Bxg3 25. fxg3 (25. h6 $4 Bf4+ $19 {this is the difference
between Kc1 and Kb3}) 25... Ne3 26. Nxe3 Rxe3 $11) 24... Bxg3 25. h6 $3 Na5+ (
25... Ne4 26. fxg3 $1 $18 Nxg5 27. h7 $18) 26. Ka4 (26. Kb2 $4 Be5+ $19) 26...
b5+ $1 {Black is complicating the things as much as he can} 27. Kxa5 Bc7+ 28.
Kxb5 (28. Ka6 $4 {It is never too late to go wrong}) 28... Rab8+ 29. Ka4 Ne4 (
29... Rb4+ 30. Ka3 Be5 31. Rb1 $18) 30. Rxd5 $1 (30. h7 $2 Nc3+ 31. Ka3 Nb5+
32. Ka4 (32. Kb2 $2 Nd4+ 33. Kc3 Ne2+ 34. Kd2 Ba5+ 35. c3 Bxc3+ 36. Kc2 Rb2+
37. Kd3 c4#) 32... Nc3+ 33. Ka3 $11) 30... Nc3+ 31. Ka3 Nb5+ 32. Kb2 Nd4+ 33.
Kc3 Nb5+ 34. Kd3 1-0

