{[%evp 0,62,19,31,68,83,76,32,33,34,38,31,37,22,41,39,32,26,43,50,38,13,60,22,
38,46,62,34,59,51,52,45,52,56,46,-16,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,128,0,98,0,0,0,0,0,-73,
-38,-166,-20,-47,-64,-66,-66,-66,-458,-472,-584,-639] The Structure exf6} 1. e4
c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ (5. Qe2 {is the recent trend in
this position}) 5... exf6 {The "f3" knight is dominating by the "f6" pawn.
This structure is very good for Black against the knight on "f3".} 6. Bc4 Qe7+
{An interesting idea. White is trying to avoid 6...Bd6 7.Qe2+} 7. Be2 Qc7 8. d4
Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. h3 {After h3, Black should already have the idea Be6+Qd7
and sacrifice on h3. Surprisingly enough Karjakin missed this idea.} Rd8 {
It is time to evaluate the position and to determine the plans. White has a
pawn majority on the queenside and his idea is to exchange as many pieces as
he can and to start pushing "c" and "d" pawns. As we see Jobava is trying to
prevent this with his last move. Black's scheme is easier to understand. The
knight's role is to defend the kingside, and Black should try to organize an
attack against Black's king. The idea of Bxh3 is always in the air. The other
typical idea is "c6-c5" break} 11. Be3 Nd7 12. c4 Nf8 {This is the best square
for the knight. We can activate it later via "g6"} 13. Bd3 Ng6 14. Qc2 Be6 15.
Rfe1 Qd7 16. Bd2 $6 (16. Bf1 $1 {was mandatory with the idea Rad1, d5. Black
should be fine after} Bf5 17. Qb3 a5 $11) 16... Bxh3 $1 17. gxh3 Qxh3 {The
position is objectively drawish, but it is clear that it is easier to play for
Black.} 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. Re3 g5 20. c5 $2 (20. Rae1 {is better and keeps
Black in the game}) 20... Bf4 21. Rb3 Bc7 22. Qc4 Qh5 $2 (22... Qg4+ 23. Kf1
Re8 $19 {[%cal Rg4h3,Re8e4]}) 23. Kg2 (23. Rxb7 {and the engine is trying to
convince me that this is equal.}) 23... Qg4+ $19 24. Kf1 Re8 25. Re1 Qh3+ 26.
Kg1 Rxe1+ 27. Bxe1 Qg4+ 28. Kf1 Re8 29. Ng1 Bh2 30. Ne2 Rxe2 31. Rxb7 Re6 {
A beautiful win by Jobava which proves that Black's setup after exf6 is quite
playable for Black especially against the knight on "f3"} 0-1

